WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.405 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.405 --> 00:00:04.810 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.810 --> 00:00:07.215 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.215 --> 00:00:11.860 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.860 --> 00:00:14.400 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK, everyone.

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:16.600 align:middle line:84%
So today, we're
going to learn some

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:19.120 align:middle line:84%
of the fundamental estimates
of projection theory

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:23.040 align:middle line:84%
for balls in the plane for
the setting of real analysis.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.700 align:middle line:90%
Two goals of the class.

00:00:24.700 --> 00:00:26.640 align:middle line:84%
The first goal is to
adapt to the techniques

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:29.200 align:middle line:84%
that we learned last
time in finite fields, so

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:32.159 align:middle line:84%
the double counting technique
and the Fourier technique,

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:34.680 align:middle line:90%
to Euclidean space.

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:36.482 align:middle line:84%
And the second goal is
to start to explore.

00:00:36.482 --> 00:00:38.440 align:middle line:84%
So there's a difference
between Euclidean space

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:40.840 align:middle line:84%
and finite fields is
that in Euclidean space,

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:44.622 align:middle line:84%
we have to pay attention to
how our sets are clustered.

00:00:44.622 --> 00:00:46.080 align:middle line:84%
And so the second
goal of the class

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:50.120 align:middle line:84%
is to start to
explore clustering--

00:00:50.120 --> 00:00:52.240 align:middle line:84%
information about how
the sets are clustered

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:55.880 align:middle line:84%
and how that comes
into the story.

00:00:55.880 --> 00:00:56.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:56.380 --> 00:01:03.682 align:middle line:90%


00:01:03.682 --> 00:01:04.980 align:middle line:90%
So here's our setup.

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:09.030 align:middle line:90%


00:01:09.030 --> 00:01:20.590 align:middle line:84%
We'll have x will be a
set of disjoint unit balls

00:01:20.590 --> 00:01:26.250 align:middle line:90%
in the ball of radius R squared.

00:01:26.250 --> 00:01:26.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:26.750 --> 00:01:30.370 align:middle line:84%
So that's our set of
points or set of balls.

00:01:30.370 --> 00:01:33.310 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to have
a set of directions called D.

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:36.870 align:middle line:90%
So D is a finite subset of S1.

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:39.730 align:middle line:90%
It's 1 over r separated.

00:01:39.730 --> 00:01:43.150 align:middle line:84%
So the distance between any
two points of D is at least 1

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:47.390 align:middle line:90%
over R.

00:01:47.390 --> 00:01:52.910 align:middle line:84%
And then S which
depends on X and D

00:01:52.910 --> 00:01:55.890 align:middle line:84%
is the maximum size
of the projection.

00:01:55.890 --> 00:01:59.860 align:middle line:84%
So I look at all
the directions in D

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:02.400 align:middle line:84%
and I project the set
X in that direction,

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:03.860 align:middle line:90%
and I take its measure.

00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:07.555 align:middle line:84%
And the maximum of
that is called S. OK.

00:02:07.555 --> 00:02:10.180 align:middle line:84%
So projection theory, we try to
understand how these things are

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:11.500 align:middle line:90%
related to each other.

00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:13.780 align:middle line:84%
And in this Euclidean
setting, we also

00:02:13.780 --> 00:02:16.460 align:middle line:84%
need to care about
how this set X

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:19.660 align:middle line:90%
and how the set D are clustered.

00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:21.880 align:middle line:90%
So that's measured by this--

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:24.420 align:middle line:84%
I guess call them
clustering functions.

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:29.220 align:middle line:84%
So N sub X of little
r is the measures--

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:33.380 align:middle line:84%
the most amount of X in any
ball of radius little r.

00:02:33.380 --> 00:02:37.980 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
maximum over C in R2

00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:43.380 align:middle line:84%
or of the size of x intersected
with the ball around c

00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:45.900 align:middle line:90%
of radius r.

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:48.020 align:middle line:84%
So this measures
how x is clustered.

00:02:48.020 --> 00:02:51.360 align:middle line:84%
And we're also going to
measure how D is clustered.

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:58.370 align:middle line:84%
So N sub D of rho is
the maximum over any--

00:02:58.370 --> 00:03:07.150 align:middle line:84%
so sigma in S1 and arc of
length rho of D intersect c.

00:03:07.150 --> 00:03:12.310 align:middle line:90%


00:03:12.310 --> 00:03:12.810 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:12.810 --> 00:03:15.330 align:middle line:90%


00:03:15.330 --> 00:03:15.830 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:18.890 align:middle line:84%
So our big goal is in
terms of this information

00:03:18.890 --> 00:03:25.790 align:middle line:84%
and how big D is and how big X
is, what can we say about S. OK.

00:03:25.790 --> 00:03:30.610 align:middle line:90%


00:03:30.610 --> 00:03:33.080 align:middle line:84%
So we're first going to do
the double counting approach.

00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:39.290 align:middle line:90%


00:03:39.290 --> 00:03:42.317 align:middle line:84%
And the argument is, in
spirit, the same as last time.

00:03:42.317 --> 00:03:44.650 align:middle line:84%
But we'll see that when we
try to do the double counting

00:03:44.650 --> 00:03:48.170 align:middle line:84%
that we did last time, that the
N sub X function and the N sub D

00:03:48.170 --> 00:03:50.290 align:middle line:84%
function will come
into the story,

00:03:50.290 --> 00:03:52.970 align:middle line:84%
and it leads to the
following bound.

00:03:52.970 --> 00:03:55.040 align:middle line:90%
So theorem one.

00:03:55.040 --> 00:03:58.600 align:middle line:84%
I'll call it theorem
1R for the real case.

00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:01.560 align:middle line:84%
Whereas last time we had
something called theorem one,

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:04.360 align:middle line:84%
which, when I do it again, it'll
be theorem 1F for the finite

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:07.440 align:middle line:84%
field case, and eventually
we'll compare them.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:07.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:07.940 --> 00:04:16.079 align:middle line:84%
So if we have this
setup, then the number

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:20.160 align:middle line:90%
of directions is bounded by--

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:20.779 align:middle line:90%
let's see.

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:27.320 align:middle line:90%


00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:27.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:29.680 align:middle line:84%
So you'll notice that
this is not a formula

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:30.800 align:middle line:90%
that I have memorized.

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:33.880 align:middle line:90%


00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:37.610 align:middle line:84%
S over X times the sum
over different scales.

00:04:37.610 --> 00:04:48.980 align:middle line:90%


00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:49.480 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:58.260 align:middle line:90%


00:04:58.260 --> 00:04:58.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:58.760 --> 00:05:00.313 align:middle line:84%
So it's a sum over
different scales,

00:05:00.313 --> 00:05:01.980 align:middle line:84%
and we often in this
class will sum over

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:06.580 align:middle line:84%
a dyadic sequence of scales,
powers of two or whatever.

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:07.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:11.400 align:middle line:84%
And so the formula doesn't
yet look that similar,

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:13.720 align:middle line:84%
but the idea is the
same as last time.

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:15.740 align:middle line:84%
And then eventually we'll
compare the formulas

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:18.260 align:middle line:84%
and see that under certain
assumptions on this

00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:21.980 align:middle line:84%
it's actually very
similar to last time.

00:05:21.980 --> 00:05:22.480 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:26.160 align:middle line:90%


00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:31.340 align:middle line:84%
So the proof is to double count
a certain quantity, which we

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:33.500 align:middle line:90%
called coincidences last time.

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:43.460 align:middle line:84%
So the key quantity called star
is the number of B1 and B2 in X.

00:05:43.460 --> 00:05:46.900 align:middle line:90%
These are unit balls.

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:49.120 align:middle line:84%
So remember, X is a
set of unit balls.

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:52.730 align:middle line:84%
So these are two
of the unit balls.

00:05:52.730 --> 00:05:56.907 align:middle line:84%
And theta and D. I
guess we'll say they're

00:05:56.907 --> 00:05:58.490 align:middle line:84%
not equal to each
other, although that

00:05:58.490 --> 00:06:00.230 align:middle line:90%
won't matter as much this time.

00:06:00.230 --> 00:06:02.810 align:middle line:90%


00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:08.610 align:middle line:84%
So that pi theta of
B1 and pi theta of B2

00:06:08.610 --> 00:06:11.290 align:middle line:90%
are similar to each other.

00:06:11.290 --> 00:06:13.005 align:middle line:84%
And in this setting,
we won't count--

00:06:13.005 --> 00:06:14.630 align:middle line:84%
they don't have to
be exactly the same.

00:06:14.630 --> 00:06:16.350 align:middle line:84%
I would just like
them to overlap.

00:06:16.350 --> 00:06:18.930 align:middle line:84%
So my condition will be that
the intersection of these

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:20.730 align:middle line:90%
is non-empty.

00:06:20.730 --> 00:06:21.860 align:middle line:90%
So that's my key quantity.

00:06:21.860 --> 00:06:29.570 align:middle line:90%


00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:32.530 align:middle line:84%
Actually, in this
setup, I'm going

00:06:32.530 --> 00:06:35.672 align:middle line:84%
to allow them to be
equal to each other.

00:06:35.672 --> 00:06:37.630 align:middle line:84%
That makes the double
counting a little easier.

00:06:37.630 --> 00:06:42.530 align:middle line:84%
And in a sense, we'll see,
it's part of what's up here.

00:06:42.530 --> 00:06:44.876 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:44.876 --> 00:06:48.790 align:middle line:84%
So there's a lower bound,
which is straightforward.

00:06:48.790 --> 00:06:51.400 align:middle line:90%


00:06:51.400 --> 00:06:56.800 align:middle line:84%
The lower bound says that
this star is at least

00:06:56.800 --> 00:07:02.360 align:middle line:84%
the number of directions times
in each direction X over S

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:07.220 align:middle line:84%
squared times S. So
in each direction,

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:09.440 align:middle line:84%
these X different
balls have been

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:12.120 align:middle line:90%
projected into only S slots.

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:16.240 align:middle line:84%
So a typical slot has X
over S balls in its fiber.

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:19.960 align:middle line:84%
And so we have this
many squared choices

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:23.240 align:middle line:84%
to pick B1 and B2
in the same fiber.

00:07:23.240 --> 00:07:24.560 align:middle line:90%
S times.

00:07:24.560 --> 00:07:29.000 align:middle line:84%
So the lower bound is really
the same as last time.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:30.335 align:middle line:90%
Same as last time.

00:07:30.335 --> 00:07:31.210 align:middle line:90%
Same as the homework.

00:07:31.210 --> 00:07:41.800 align:middle line:90%


00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:42.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:44.150 align:middle line:84%
So now let's look
at the upper bound.

00:07:44.150 --> 00:07:51.110 align:middle line:90%


00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:55.950 align:middle line:84%
So I will-- for
now I'll fix B1, B2

00:07:55.950 --> 00:08:03.950 align:middle line:84%
and I'll say that the distance
between B1 and B2 is around r.

00:08:03.950 --> 00:08:09.830 align:middle line:84%
So here is my picture B1
and B2 and the distance

00:08:09.830 --> 00:08:12.710 align:middle line:90%
between them is around r.

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:13.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:13.430 --> 00:08:15.710 align:middle line:84%
So now I'm interested
in projections

00:08:15.710 --> 00:08:19.910 align:middle line:84%
where the projection of B1 and
the projection of B2 overlap.

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:23.110 align:middle line:84%
And so the angles
for those projections

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:26.750 align:middle line:90%
are in a little angular range.

00:08:26.750 --> 00:08:29.970 align:middle line:84%
The angle of the projection must
be somewhere in this range here.

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:32.750 align:middle line:90%


00:08:32.750 --> 00:08:37.429 align:middle line:84%
So what I'll say
is let's say that v

00:08:37.429 --> 00:08:40.789 align:middle line:90%
is the direction from B1 to B2.

00:08:40.789 --> 00:08:46.750 align:middle line:84%
So v is center of
B2 minus center

00:08:46.750 --> 00:08:49.920 align:middle line:84%
of center B1 over
the norm of that.

00:08:49.920 --> 00:08:54.020 align:middle line:90%


00:08:54.020 --> 00:09:03.220 align:middle line:84%
And if pi theta of B1 intersect
pi theta B2 is not empty,

00:09:03.220 --> 00:09:07.660 align:middle line:84%
then theta must be
pretty close to v.

00:09:07.660 --> 00:09:13.100 align:middle line:84%
What I'll say is that the
angle between theta and v

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:15.560 align:middle line:90%
is smaller than around 1 over r.

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:25.700 align:middle line:90%


00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:28.580 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:28.580 --> 00:09:35.860 align:middle line:84%
So now the number of theta so
that pi theta of B1 intersect pi

00:09:35.860 --> 00:09:37.570 align:middle line:90%
theta of B2 is not empty.

00:09:37.570 --> 00:09:41.980 align:middle line:90%


00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:44.620 align:middle line:84%
That would be bounded by,
well, the number of directions

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:46.330 align:middle line:90%
in this little arc.

00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:49.970 align:middle line:90%
So that would be ND of 1 over r.

00:09:49.970 --> 00:09:54.330 align:middle line:84%
So we see the spacing
function of the set D

00:09:54.330 --> 00:09:55.590 align:middle line:90%
comes into play here.

00:09:55.590 --> 00:09:58.510 align:middle line:90%


00:09:58.510 --> 00:09:59.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:02.810 align:middle line:84%
So that's what happens
when we fixed B1 and B2.

00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:05.737 align:middle line:84%
And the case B1
equals B2 is allowed.

00:10:05.737 --> 00:10:07.570 align:middle line:84%
And I'll make this
slightly funny convention

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:10.850 align:middle line:84%
that then r is one unit ball,
so the distance between them

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:12.050 align:middle line:90%
is one.

00:10:12.050 --> 00:10:13.890 align:middle line:90%
And this is true, then.

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:17.410 align:middle line:84%
I mean, v is not well
defined, but this condition

00:10:17.410 --> 00:10:20.270 align:middle line:84%
includes the whole range
of angles, so it's true.

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:25.442 align:middle line:90%


00:10:25.442 --> 00:10:33.290 align:middle line:84%
So remark if B1 equals B2,
take little r equals 1.

00:10:33.290 --> 00:10:37.070 align:middle line:84%
It's slightly exceptional
but all the bounds are true.

00:10:37.070 --> 00:10:43.920 align:middle line:90%


00:10:43.920 --> 00:10:45.480 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:49.480 align:middle line:84%
So if we want to
upper bound star,

00:10:49.480 --> 00:10:52.850 align:middle line:84%
now we need to count the number
of choices for B1 and B2.

00:10:52.850 --> 00:10:55.960 align:middle line:90%


00:10:55.960 --> 00:11:02.240 align:middle line:84%
So now I'm interested in the
number of pairs, B1, B2, and x

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:07.280 align:middle line:84%
with the property that
the distance from B1 to B2

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:10.040 align:middle line:90%
is at most r.

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:10.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:12.040 align:middle line:90%
How big is that?

00:11:12.040 --> 00:11:17.640 align:middle line:84%
Well, I have norm
of X choices for B1.

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:20.520 align:middle line:84%
But once I choose B1, I don't
have all that many choices

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:24.040 align:middle line:84%
for B2 because B2 has
to be close to B1.

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:27.000 align:middle line:90%
It has to be in a little r ball.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.560 align:middle line:84%
So the number of choices
for B2 is at most NX of r.

00:11:31.560 --> 00:11:34.660 align:middle line:84%
So at this moment, the spacing
function of X comes into play.

00:11:34.660 --> 00:11:39.160 align:middle line:90%


00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:39.852 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:39.852 --> 00:11:44.190 align:middle line:84%
So now we can combine
these to upper bound star.

00:11:44.190 --> 00:11:55.710 align:middle line:84%
So star is now upper bounded by
X times NX of r times ND of 1

00:11:55.710 --> 00:11:58.242 align:middle line:90%
over r.

00:11:58.242 --> 00:11:59.230 align:middle line:90%
Ah, sorry.

00:11:59.230 --> 00:12:08.270 align:middle line:84%
So star is upper bounded by
the sum over the dyadic r

00:12:08.270 --> 00:12:09.320 align:middle line:90%
of this quantity.

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:15.070 align:middle line:90%


00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:15.976 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:15.976 --> 00:12:18.350 align:middle line:90%
So let me say why.

00:12:18.350 --> 00:12:22.830 align:middle line:84%
So star is this set
of coincidences.

00:12:22.830 --> 00:12:27.550 align:middle line:84%
It's a B1 and B2 and a theta,
and for each coincidence,

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:29.590 align:middle line:84%
I sort these coincidences
by the distance

00:12:29.590 --> 00:12:32.150 align:middle line:90%
from B1 to B2, which I call r.

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:36.110 align:middle line:84%
So I take the coincidences where
the distance is around r and I

00:12:36.110 --> 00:12:38.110 align:middle line:90%
sum over the possible r's.

00:12:38.110 --> 00:12:44.580 align:middle line:84%
Once I fixed r, I have this many
choices for the pair B1, B2.

00:12:44.580 --> 00:12:47.870 align:middle line:84%
And once I've fixed B1 and
B2, I have this many choices

00:12:47.870 --> 00:12:48.370 align:middle line:90%
for theta.

00:12:48.370 --> 00:12:51.820 align:middle line:90%


00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:52.730 align:middle line:90%
So that's the point.

00:12:52.730 --> 00:12:55.900 align:middle line:90%


00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:57.596 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:57.596 --> 00:12:59.060 align:middle line:90%
The rest is algebra.

00:12:59.060 --> 00:13:00.560 align:middle line:84%
I'll sketch it
quickly on the board,

00:13:00.560 --> 00:13:02.060 align:middle line:84%
and that'll be the
end of the proof.

00:13:02.060 --> 00:13:05.540 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll pause
to digest and check it.

00:13:05.540 --> 00:13:06.040 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:06.040 --> 00:13:11.060 align:middle line:84%
So all together,
we have X squared S

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:14.900 align:middle line:84%
inverse D is bounded
by star which

00:13:14.900 --> 00:13:23.300 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by the sum
over r dyadic of X and X

00:13:23.300 --> 00:13:26.900 align:middle line:90%
of r and D of 1 over r.

00:13:26.900 --> 00:13:28.830 align:middle line:84%
And then I just get
the D by itself.

00:13:28.830 --> 00:13:34.620 align:middle line:90%


00:13:34.620 --> 00:13:37.000 align:middle line:84%
If you move this stuff
over to the other side,

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:38.400 align:middle line:84%
you get the formula
on the board.

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:42.920 align:middle line:90%


00:13:42.920 --> 00:13:43.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:46.710 align:middle line:84%
So let's pause there for
questions and comments.

00:13:46.710 --> 00:14:07.560 align:middle line:90%


00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:09.200 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:09.200 --> 00:14:09.700 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:15.200 align:middle line:84%
So I wanted to get
a sense of start

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:18.040 align:middle line:84%
to explore this function
NX of r by looking

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:20.080 align:middle line:84%
at a few different
examples of sets X

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:22.080 align:middle line:84%
and writing down
what is NX of r.

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:24.520 align:middle line:84%
It's not difficult, but having
a few different examples

00:14:24.520 --> 00:14:29.240 align:middle line:84%
in our mind will help to
orient us as we keep going.

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:31.980 align:middle line:84%
And actually will help also
to digest this formula.

00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:33.860 align:middle line:90%
So this proof was clean.

00:14:33.860 --> 00:14:35.760 align:middle line:84%
This formula is a
little bit messy.

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:37.460 align:middle line:84%
So after looking
at some examples,

00:14:37.460 --> 00:14:40.312 align:middle line:84%
we'll will digest this formula
and think about a situation

00:14:40.312 --> 00:14:42.020 align:middle line:84%
where it works out a
little more cleanly.

00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:45.150 align:middle line:90%


00:14:45.150 --> 00:14:45.810 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:14:45.810 --> 00:14:56.750 align:middle line:90%


00:14:56.750 --> 00:14:57.490 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:14:57.490 --> 00:15:03.590 align:middle line:90%
So examples for N sub X of r.

00:15:03.590 --> 00:15:04.282 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:04.282 --> 00:15:12.150 align:middle line:84%
So number one, X is the one
neighborhood of a curve,

00:15:12.150 --> 00:15:14.710 align:middle line:84%
like a circle or
parabola or something.

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:16.910 align:middle line:90%
So here's the ball of radius r.

00:15:16.910 --> 00:15:19.190 align:middle line:84%
And inside of there,
I have a nice curve.

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:26.230 align:middle line:84%
And all along the curve I
have unit balls max X. So

00:15:26.230 --> 00:15:29.870 align:middle line:84%
if I have this set, how
many unit balls do I have

00:15:29.870 --> 00:15:32.750 align:middle line:90%
in a ball of radius little r?

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:34.250 align:middle line:90%
That would be around r.

00:15:34.250 --> 00:15:38.460 align:middle line:90%


00:15:38.460 --> 00:15:40.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:40.660 --> 00:15:41.730 align:middle line:90%
Do a second example.

00:15:41.730 --> 00:15:44.940 align:middle line:90%


00:15:44.940 --> 00:15:48.060 align:middle line:84%
Second example would
be very spread out.

00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:51.660 align:middle line:84%
If you imagine that these
points are positive charges that

00:15:51.660 --> 00:15:56.220 align:middle line:84%
repel each other, and they push
as far away from each other as

00:15:56.220 --> 00:15:58.740 align:middle line:84%
possible, they would arrange
themselves in something

00:15:58.740 --> 00:16:02.740 align:middle line:90%
like a lattice inside of here.

00:16:02.740 --> 00:16:03.240 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:07.940 align:middle line:84%
So I'll call this the well
spaced example, the most spread

00:16:07.940 --> 00:16:09.540 align:middle line:90%
out example.

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:10.920 align:middle line:90%
So it looks like this.

00:16:10.920 --> 00:16:18.380 align:middle line:90%


00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:24.020 align:middle line:84%
So it's let's say it's a
well spaced n by n grid.

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:28.340 align:middle line:84%
And so the distance
between neighboring balls

00:16:28.340 --> 00:16:37.050 align:middle line:84%
would be like r over N. So now
what would NX of r be like.

00:16:37.050 --> 00:16:40.570 align:middle line:84%
Well, it would be one
for quite a while.

00:16:40.570 --> 00:16:46.330 align:middle line:84%
If our radius is less than r
over N, then this would be 1.

00:16:46.330 --> 00:16:48.510 align:middle line:84%
But then eventually, as
the radius gets bigger,

00:16:48.510 --> 00:16:50.070 align:middle line:90%
it would get bigger than 1.

00:16:50.070 --> 00:16:54.250 align:middle line:84%
And at that point, it
would be its fair share

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:57.370 align:middle line:84%
of the total number
or total size of X.

00:16:57.370 --> 00:16:59.630 align:middle line:84%
So once r is bigger
than this threshold,

00:16:59.630 --> 00:17:03.010 align:middle line:84%
every little r ball contains
the same amount of X.

00:17:03.010 --> 00:17:07.569 align:middle line:84%
And so the density of X is
like N squared over r squared.

00:17:07.569 --> 00:17:09.470 align:middle line:84%
The area of the
ball is like this.

00:17:09.470 --> 00:17:15.849 align:middle line:90%


00:17:15.849 --> 00:17:17.229 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:17:17.229 --> 00:17:20.569 align:middle line:84%
And I'll do a third
example, which

00:17:20.569 --> 00:17:25.970 align:middle line:84%
is the points could
be very clustered.

00:17:25.970 --> 00:17:27.849 align:middle line:90%
Cluster.

00:17:27.849 --> 00:17:38.160 align:middle line:84%
So we could have N squared
unit balls in an N ball.

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:40.480 align:middle line:84%
So the picture
would be like this.

00:17:40.480 --> 00:17:42.800 align:middle line:90%
We have our ball of radius r.

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:45.980 align:middle line:84%
Inside of there we have a
smaller ball of radius N,

00:17:45.980 --> 00:17:52.680 align:middle line:84%
and we pack the smaller
ball with unit balls of X.

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:56.060 align:middle line:90%
So now what is N sub X of r?

00:17:56.060 --> 00:17:59.000 align:middle line:90%


00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, it grows like
r squared until r

00:18:03.320 --> 00:18:06.280 align:middle line:90%
is as big as this N ball.

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:08.522 align:middle line:84%
And after that, there are
only N squared balls at all

00:18:08.522 --> 00:18:09.980 align:middle line:84%
so you can make it
a little bigger.

00:18:09.980 --> 00:18:11.900 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't grow anymore.

00:18:11.900 --> 00:18:22.473 align:middle line:84%
So it caps off it N squared
if r is bigger than N.

00:18:22.473 --> 00:18:22.973 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:22.973 --> 00:18:26.424 align:middle line:90%


00:18:26.424 --> 00:18:33.350 align:middle line:84%
So now I will draw some pictures
of these three functions.

00:18:33.350 --> 00:18:34.490 align:middle line:90%
You can compare them.

00:18:34.490 --> 00:18:47.630 align:middle line:90%


00:18:47.630 --> 00:18:48.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:48.590 --> 00:18:49.620 align:middle line:90%
We'll do some pictures.

00:18:49.620 --> 00:18:52.990 align:middle line:90%


00:18:52.990 --> 00:18:57.070 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to normalize in my
pictures, I have to choose an N.

00:18:57.070 --> 00:19:00.910 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to choose N
equals r to the 1/2.

00:19:00.910 --> 00:19:03.470 align:middle line:84%
That's helpful because it
says that the total size of X

00:19:03.470 --> 00:19:05.610 align:middle line:84%
is around r in all
three examples.

00:19:05.610 --> 00:19:08.790 align:middle line:84%
It makes them a little easier
to compare with each other.

00:19:08.790 --> 00:19:09.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:09.290 --> 00:19:11.230 align:middle line:90%
So now I'll make a graph.

00:19:11.230 --> 00:19:13.750 align:middle line:84%
Basically, I'd like to
put on this axis little r

00:19:13.750 --> 00:19:16.990 align:middle line:84%
and on this axis N
sub X of little r.

00:19:16.990 --> 00:19:19.330 align:middle line:84%
But this graph, like
many graphs in math,

00:19:19.330 --> 00:19:22.710 align:middle line:84%
looks nicer if we
use a log log plot.

00:19:22.710 --> 00:19:26.670 align:middle line:84%
So on this axis, I'm going
to put the log of little r.

00:19:26.670 --> 00:19:31.420 align:middle line:84%
And the nicest base for that is
big R. This goes from 0 to 1.

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:36.020 align:middle line:84%
And on this axis, I'm going to
put the log of N sub X of r.

00:19:36.020 --> 00:19:38.620 align:middle line:84%
And it's natural to
use the same base.

00:19:38.620 --> 00:19:40.980 align:middle line:90%
So this goes from 0 to 1.

00:19:40.980 --> 00:19:42.640 align:middle line:84%
This could go above
one potentially,

00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:44.940 align:middle line:84%
but because the size
of X happens to be r,

00:19:44.940 --> 00:19:46.200 align:middle line:90%
we're going to stop there.

00:19:46.200 --> 00:19:48.840 align:middle line:90%


00:19:48.840 --> 00:19:52.260 align:middle line:84%
So now what do these
three examples look like.

00:19:52.260 --> 00:19:54.110 align:middle line:84%
The first example
is a straight line.

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:56.900 align:middle line:90%


00:19:56.900 --> 00:19:58.200 align:middle line:90%
So that's example one.

00:19:58.200 --> 00:20:06.420 align:middle line:90%


00:20:06.420 --> 00:20:09.180 align:middle line:84%
The second example
grows more slowly

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:12.340 align:middle line:84%
than the straight
line for a while.

00:20:12.340 --> 00:20:14.180 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't grow at
all for a while.

00:20:14.180 --> 00:20:18.260 align:middle line:84%
And then it grows
quickly to catch up.

00:20:18.260 --> 00:20:19.900 align:middle line:90%
So that's the second example.

00:20:19.900 --> 00:20:22.980 align:middle line:90%
It lies below the straight line.

00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:26.740 align:middle line:84%
And then the third
example grows more quickly

00:20:26.740 --> 00:20:30.930 align:middle line:84%
than the first example, and
then it reaches a certain point

00:20:30.930 --> 00:20:32.810 align:middle line:90%
and it stops growing.

00:20:32.810 --> 00:20:34.250 align:middle line:90%
So it looks like this.

00:20:34.250 --> 00:20:36.030 align:middle line:84%
And it lies above
the straight line.

00:20:36.030 --> 00:20:42.450 align:middle line:90%


00:20:42.450 --> 00:20:43.818 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:43.818 --> 00:20:46.370 align:middle line:84%
So in this theory,
there turns out

00:20:46.370 --> 00:20:48.490 align:middle line:90%
to be that things that grow--

00:20:48.490 --> 00:20:51.810 align:middle line:84%
the straight line case
is an important case.

00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:53.730 align:middle line:84%
And then there's an
important distinction

00:20:53.730 --> 00:20:56.450 align:middle line:84%
between things that are below
the straight line, things that

00:20:56.450 --> 00:20:57.790 align:middle line:90%
are above the straight line.

00:20:57.790 --> 00:21:02.090 align:middle line:90%


00:21:02.090 --> 00:21:12.370 align:middle line:84%
So the straight line
case would be that N--

00:21:12.370 --> 00:21:16.090 align:middle line:84%
that the size of X
would be r to the alpha

00:21:16.090 --> 00:21:20.370 align:middle line:84%
for some alpha, and then
N sub little r of X or N

00:21:20.370 --> 00:21:25.730 align:middle line:84%
sub X of little r would
be little r to the alpha.

00:21:25.730 --> 00:21:29.200 align:middle line:84%
That would be the
straight line case.

00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:42.320 align:middle line:84%
And the below the
straight line case,

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:45.080 align:middle line:90%
X would still be R to the alpha.

00:21:45.080 --> 00:21:46.885 align:middle line:84%
So the end point
would be the same,

00:21:46.885 --> 00:21:48.760 align:middle line:84%
but now in the middle
we're going to go below

00:21:48.760 --> 00:21:50.040 align:middle line:90%
what we had before.

00:21:50.040 --> 00:21:55.140 align:middle line:84%
So N sub X of r would be
at most r to the alpha.

00:21:55.140 --> 00:22:00.520 align:middle line:90%


00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:01.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:01.780 --> 00:22:07.760 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is called
a regular alpha dimensional

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:10.560 align:middle line:90%
spacing.

00:22:10.560 --> 00:22:14.090 align:middle line:84%
And this thing is called
alpha dimensional spacing.

00:22:14.090 --> 00:22:27.840 align:middle line:90%


00:22:27.840 --> 00:22:29.600 align:middle line:84%
I'd like to make
one more definition.

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:39.740 align:middle line:84%
I'll say that X has
Hausdorff spacing

00:22:39.740 --> 00:22:43.720 align:middle line:84%
if it has alpha dimensional
spacing for some alpha.

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:47.780 align:middle line:90%


00:22:47.780 --> 00:22:49.660 align:middle line:84%
But another way
of saying that is

00:22:49.660 --> 00:22:54.940 align:middle line:84%
if you look at how many points
of X are in a ball of radius R

00:22:54.940 --> 00:22:59.900 align:middle line:84%
to the beta, it's bounded by
the total number of points of X

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:00.490 align:middle line:90%
to the beta.

00:23:00.490 --> 00:23:04.740 align:middle line:90%


00:23:04.740 --> 00:23:06.160 align:middle line:90%
And this is equivalent.

00:23:06.160 --> 00:23:08.280 align:middle line:84%
This is still below
the straight line.

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:21.800 align:middle line:90%


00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:22.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:22.300 --> 00:23:26.670 align:middle line:84%
So over here we
have example one.

00:23:26.670 --> 00:23:28.090 align:middle line:84%
And in general,
if you have any--

00:23:28.090 --> 00:23:31.588 align:middle line:84%
if you have a submanifold
in any dimensional space,

00:23:31.588 --> 00:23:32.630 align:middle line:90%
it will behave like this.

00:23:32.630 --> 00:23:35.530 align:middle line:84%
And alpha is the dimension
of the submanifold.

00:23:35.530 --> 00:23:39.370 align:middle line:84%
Also some self-similar
Cantor set kind of fractals,

00:23:39.370 --> 00:23:41.530 align:middle line:84%
like the Cantor
set, have this kind

00:23:41.530 --> 00:23:44.530 align:middle line:84%
of spacing where alpha would
be the dimension of your Cantor

00:23:44.530 --> 00:23:45.730 align:middle line:90%
set.

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:47.510 align:middle line:84%
That's why it's called
alpha dimensional.

00:23:47.510 --> 00:23:51.930 align:middle line:90%


00:23:51.930 --> 00:23:55.770 align:middle line:84%
And these things, this thing
called Hausdorff spacing,

00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:58.370 align:middle line:84%
I called it that because
it appears naturally

00:23:58.370 --> 00:24:00.310 align:middle line:84%
in the theory of
Hausdorff dimensions.

00:24:00.310 --> 00:24:06.750 align:middle line:90%


00:24:06.750 --> 00:24:07.250 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:24:07.250 --> 00:24:08.930 align:middle line:84%
So it's maybe worth
saying briefly

00:24:08.930 --> 00:24:11.017 align:middle line:84%
that in the geometric
measure theory literature,

00:24:11.017 --> 00:24:12.850 align:middle line:84%
a lot of the stuff we're
talking about today

00:24:12.850 --> 00:24:15.730 align:middle line:84%
was originally described in
the language of Hausdorff

00:24:15.730 --> 00:24:17.850 align:middle line:90%
dimensions.

00:24:17.850 --> 00:24:22.640 align:middle line:84%
But my impression is that
that's not really that helpful.

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:25.063 align:middle line:84%
Like, if we defined
Hausdorff dimensions,

00:24:25.063 --> 00:24:26.480 align:middle line:84%
and then we wanted
to prove things

00:24:26.480 --> 00:24:28.760 align:middle line:84%
about Hausdorff
dimensions, we would add

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:31.800 align:middle line:90%
an extra layer of definition.

00:24:31.800 --> 00:24:35.240 align:middle line:84%
And then we'd have to check
the extra layer of definition.

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:37.580 align:middle line:84%
But then in all the applications
that we'll talk about,

00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:39.260 align:middle line:84%
we would never use
those definitions.

00:24:39.260 --> 00:24:41.640 align:middle line:84%
We would go back to this
theorem the way it's stated now

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:43.720 align:middle line:90%
and use that.

00:24:43.720 --> 00:24:48.000 align:middle line:84%
So I have-- a bit tentatively,
but I've come to the conclusion

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.120 align:middle line:84%
that Hausdorff
dimension is not really

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:52.920 align:middle line:84%
a helpful notion
for this subject.

00:24:52.920 --> 00:24:55.100 align:middle line:84%
And so I'm going
to leave it out.

00:24:55.100 --> 00:24:59.600 align:middle line:90%


00:24:59.600 --> 00:25:00.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:00.860 --> 00:25:05.400 align:middle line:84%
But any questions or comments
about these different ways

00:25:05.400 --> 00:25:06.570 align:middle line:90%
that a set can be spaced.

00:25:06.570 --> 00:25:09.320 align:middle line:90%


00:25:09.320 --> 00:25:09.920 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:14.840 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I'm wondering,
like in the theorem one

00:25:14.840 --> 00:25:18.760 align:middle line:84%
for the lower bound,
basically, if we

00:25:18.760 --> 00:25:24.390 align:middle line:84%
try to calculate lower
bound for V1, V2,

00:25:24.390 --> 00:25:32.690 align:middle line:84%
is this somehow r from
R1 to R2, like that,

00:25:32.690 --> 00:25:36.070 align:middle line:84%
and compare this
with the upper bound

00:25:36.070 --> 00:25:39.850 align:middle line:84%
would be the distance
from V1 and V2

00:25:39.850 --> 00:25:45.520 align:middle line:84%
that gives more information
than the inequality?

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:46.450 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:25:46.450 --> 00:25:46.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:46.950 --> 00:25:49.910 align:middle line:84%
So the question is,
when we were processing

00:25:49.910 --> 00:25:51.830 align:middle line:84%
the upper bound for
this, we sorted it

00:25:51.830 --> 00:25:53.470 align:middle line:90%
according to the distance.

00:25:53.470 --> 00:25:55.270 align:middle line:84%
So we really have
a set star sub r

00:25:55.270 --> 00:25:58.590 align:middle line:84%
where we add the condition
that the distance from V1 to V2

00:25:58.590 --> 00:25:59.990 align:middle line:90%
is around r.

00:25:59.990 --> 00:26:02.470 align:middle line:84%
And the question is if we
looked at the lower bound

00:26:02.470 --> 00:26:06.970 align:middle line:84%
we could also sort it by r,
and would that be helpful.

00:26:06.970 --> 00:26:07.470 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:26:07.470 --> 00:26:10.550 align:middle line:90%


00:26:10.550 --> 00:26:11.070 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:26:11.070 --> 00:26:12.910 align:middle line:84%
That is a good
thing to look into.

00:26:12.910 --> 00:26:15.420 align:middle line:84%
Off the top of my head, I don't
know if it would be helpful.

00:26:15.420 --> 00:26:18.670 align:middle line:90%


00:26:18.670 --> 00:26:24.260 align:middle line:84%
Our lower bound with this S here
depends on taking all of them,

00:26:24.260 --> 00:26:25.600 align:middle line:90%
but it would be interesting.

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:27.475 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it would be
interesting to think about.

00:26:27.475 --> 00:26:30.300 align:middle line:90%


00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:31.490 align:middle line:90%
Other questions or comments?

00:26:31.490 --> 00:26:39.580 align:middle line:90%


00:26:39.580 --> 00:26:40.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:40.180 --> 00:26:40.680 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:43.260 align:middle line:90%
So let me show you.

00:26:43.260 --> 00:26:44.620 align:middle line:90%
So I claim--

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:45.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:49.580 align:middle line:84%
It seems that this
spacing condition,

00:26:49.580 --> 00:26:52.900 align:middle line:84%
say Hausdorff spacing,
is helpful in the theory.

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:55.900 align:middle line:84%
And one way that comes about
is that a lot of the theorem

00:26:55.900 --> 00:27:01.820 align:middle line:84%
statements become a lot cleaner
if you put in Hausdorff space.

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:04.100 align:middle line:90%
So let's do that here.

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:08.100 align:middle line:84%
Let's suppose that X and
D have Hausdorff spacing.

00:27:08.100 --> 00:27:10.240 align:middle line:84%
We'll use that to
simplify this thing.

00:27:10.240 --> 00:27:33.090 align:middle line:90%


00:27:33.090 --> 00:27:33.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:33.870 --> 00:27:42.010 align:middle line:84%
So corollary one, real, is
that if we have the setup

00:27:42.010 --> 00:27:50.330 align:middle line:84%
and X and D are
Hausdorff spacing, then

00:27:50.330 --> 00:27:53.770 align:middle line:84%
we get a simpler inequality,
which matches quite well what

00:27:53.770 --> 00:27:56.250 align:middle line:90%
happens in finite fields.

00:27:56.250 --> 00:28:09.870 align:middle line:84%
Then D is bounded by S
plus X. So let me check.

00:28:09.870 --> 00:28:34.840 align:middle line:90%


00:28:34.840 --> 00:28:37.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:37.340 --> 00:28:40.440 align:middle line:84%
So I'll prove this and
then I'll try to argue.

00:28:40.440 --> 00:28:41.620 align:middle line:90%
Actually, so OK.

00:28:41.620 --> 00:28:43.380 align:middle line:84%
So this looks a little
nicer than before.

00:28:43.380 --> 00:28:46.400 align:middle line:84%
It might still not
look that nice to you.

00:28:46.400 --> 00:28:48.920 align:middle line:84%
But I would summarize
it like this.

00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:55.880 align:middle line:90%


00:28:55.880 --> 00:29:02.520 align:middle line:84%
Either S is pretty close to
X or D is smaller than S.

00:29:02.520 --> 00:29:04.580 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we
had in finite fields.

00:29:04.580 --> 00:29:05.760 align:middle line:90%
So why is it?

00:29:05.760 --> 00:29:09.500 align:middle line:84%
If S is a lot smaller than
X, this is much less than 1,

00:29:09.500 --> 00:29:11.140 align:middle line:90%
so we can rearrange that.

00:29:11.140 --> 00:29:25.310 align:middle line:84%
And we get that
D is less than S.

00:29:25.310 --> 00:29:25.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:25.910 --> 00:29:27.790 align:middle line:90%
So what's the proof?

00:29:27.790 --> 00:29:35.750 align:middle line:84%
Well, we're going to have an
expression like NX of r ND of 1

00:29:35.750 --> 00:29:36.350 align:middle line:90%
over r.

00:29:36.350 --> 00:29:39.270 align:middle line:90%


00:29:39.270 --> 00:29:44.500 align:middle line:84%
And so now let's suppose that
little r is big R to the beta.

00:29:44.500 --> 00:29:47.690 align:middle line:90%


00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:52.190 align:middle line:90%
And then being Hausdorff.

00:29:52.190 --> 00:30:01.990 align:middle line:84%
It tells us that NX of r to the
beta ND of r to the minus beta

00:30:01.990 --> 00:30:06.910 align:middle line:84%
there, that is bounded
by X to the beta times D

00:30:06.910 --> 00:30:10.430 align:middle line:90%
to the 1 minus beta.

00:30:10.430 --> 00:30:14.260 align:middle line:84%
That's what being
Hausdorff tells us.

00:30:14.260 --> 00:30:18.180 align:middle line:84%
So being Hausdorff allows us
to relate NX of r for any r

00:30:18.180 --> 00:30:23.620 align:middle line:84%
to the size of X, which is NX
or big R. And algebraically it

00:30:23.620 --> 00:30:28.620 align:middle line:84%
works out like this, and for
D, it works out like that.

00:30:28.620 --> 00:30:29.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:34.220 align:middle line:84%
And then by [? AM-GM, ?] this
is smaller than X plus D.

00:30:34.220 --> 00:30:36.300 align:middle line:84%
So every one of these
complicated things,

00:30:36.300 --> 00:30:41.540 align:middle line:84%
they're all bounded by X plus D.
And the number of them is only

00:30:41.540 --> 00:30:42.660 align:middle line:90%
log of r.

00:30:42.660 --> 00:30:43.560 align:middle line:90%
So OK, sorry.

00:30:43.560 --> 00:30:45.280 align:middle line:90%
So I should put a log of r here.

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:52.640 align:middle line:90%


00:30:52.640 --> 00:30:53.140 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:53.140 --> 00:30:56.300 align:middle line:84%
So now we're just going
to plug this in up there.

00:30:56.300 --> 00:31:01.780 align:middle line:84%
I'll have an X plus D up
there and a log r factor.

00:31:01.780 --> 00:31:06.100 align:middle line:84%
The X and the X plus D gives me
this, and the D and the X plus D

00:31:06.100 --> 00:31:07.257 align:middle line:90%
gives me that.

00:31:07.257 --> 00:31:08.090 align:middle line:90%
That's just algebra.

00:31:08.090 --> 00:31:22.660 align:middle line:90%


00:31:22.660 --> 00:31:23.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:25.560 align:middle line:84%
Now let's compare this
with the theorem we proved

00:31:25.560 --> 00:31:28.280 align:middle line:90%
last time in finite fields.

00:31:28.280 --> 00:31:36.280 align:middle line:84%
So theorem one in finite fields
said that if we had X in Fq2

00:31:36.280 --> 00:31:47.760 align:middle line:84%
and D in Fq and S is the maximum
theta in D size of pi theta of X

00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:58.880 align:middle line:84%
then either S is around
X or D is bounded by S.

00:31:58.880 --> 00:32:03.500 align:middle line:84%
And the numerology is now
the same in finite fields,

00:32:03.500 --> 00:32:06.090 align:middle line:84%
or if you have balls,
with the Hausdorff space.

00:32:06.090 --> 00:32:15.110 align:middle line:90%


00:32:15.110 --> 00:32:16.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:16.520 --> 00:32:19.110 align:middle line:84%
So in general, the
numerology in a lot of things

00:32:19.110 --> 00:32:21.790 align:middle line:84%
is the same between
finite fields and balls

00:32:21.790 --> 00:32:23.510 align:middle line:90%
with Hausdorff spacing.

00:32:23.510 --> 00:32:25.625 align:middle line:90%
And so now I'll--

00:32:25.625 --> 00:32:27.250 align:middle line:84%
so this was theorem
one from last time.

00:32:27.250 --> 00:32:29.333 align:middle line:84%
I'll track through also
theorem two from last time

00:32:29.333 --> 00:32:30.970 align:middle line:84%
and the conjecture
from last time.

00:32:30.970 --> 00:32:33.210 align:middle line:84%
And we'll see that
they all match up.

00:32:33.210 --> 00:32:58.190 align:middle line:90%


00:32:58.190 --> 00:32:59.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:59.570 --> 00:33:21.500 align:middle line:84%
So we have projection theory
in Fq2 versus unit balls in B2R

00:33:21.500 --> 00:33:24.640 align:middle line:90%
and B2R with Hausdorff space.

00:33:24.640 --> 00:33:29.940 align:middle line:90%


00:33:29.940 --> 00:33:35.860 align:middle line:84%
So here was theorem two
last time in finite fields.

00:33:35.860 --> 00:33:47.460 align:middle line:84%
So if we have our finite field
setup, which is over here,

00:33:47.460 --> 00:33:55.180 align:middle line:84%
and S is smaller than
q, then the conclusion

00:33:55.180 --> 00:34:02.260 align:middle line:84%
is that the number of directions
is smaller than Sq over X.

00:34:02.260 --> 00:34:06.740 align:middle line:84%
And here's what we'll prove
in the real case corollary 2R.

00:34:06.740 --> 00:34:12.409 align:middle line:84%
So if we have our setup
of the day and X and D are

00:34:12.409 --> 00:34:24.770 align:middle line:84%
Hausdorff and S is a
good bit smaller than R,

00:34:24.770 --> 00:34:27.550 align:middle line:84%
then maybe this needs
a little bit more.

00:34:27.550 --> 00:34:32.250 align:middle line:90%


00:34:32.250 --> 00:34:42.594 align:middle line:84%
Then D is smaller
than SR over X. OK.

00:34:42.594 --> 00:34:45.810 align:middle line:84%
So I use this symbol
with the extra tilde.

00:34:45.810 --> 00:34:49.330 align:middle line:84%
That's hiding something like a
log factor, similar to the log

00:34:49.330 --> 00:34:50.949 align:middle line:90%
factor that appeared over here.

00:34:50.949 --> 00:34:54.889 align:middle line:84%
Like, if you compare
the real case theorem

00:34:54.889 --> 00:34:59.710 align:middle line:84%
one and the finite field case,
we lost an extra log r factor.

00:34:59.710 --> 00:35:03.370 align:middle line:90%
That will happen sometimes.

00:35:03.370 --> 00:35:05.080 align:middle line:90%
So notation.

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:08.880 align:middle line:90%


00:35:08.880 --> 00:35:16.880 align:middle line:84%
A less than some B means for
every epsilon bigger than 0,

00:35:16.880 --> 00:35:19.360 align:middle line:90%
there exists C epsilon.

00:35:19.360 --> 00:35:22.710 align:middle line:84%
So A is less than or equal to
C epsilon R to the epsilon.

00:35:22.710 --> 00:35:30.660 align:middle line:90%


00:35:30.660 --> 00:35:36.600 align:middle line:84%
But if you compare these,
q corresponds to R.

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:37.380 align:middle line:90%
That makes sense.

00:35:37.380 --> 00:35:39.960 align:middle line:84%
There are q squared
points here and there

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:41.900 align:middle line:90%
are r squared unit balls here.

00:35:41.900 --> 00:35:45.080 align:middle line:90%


00:35:45.080 --> 00:35:47.240 align:middle line:84%
And these basically match
up except that there's

00:35:47.240 --> 00:35:51.480 align:middle line:90%
a minor loss here.

00:35:51.480 --> 00:35:52.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:52.440 --> 00:35:54.760 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
the Fourier method

00:35:54.760 --> 00:35:58.160 align:middle line:84%
that we'll turn to
in a little bit.

00:35:58.160 --> 00:36:01.840 align:middle line:84%
There is also a conjecture
about the sharp behavior.

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:03.960 align:middle line:90%
So conjecture.

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:12.270 align:middle line:84%
If p is prime and we have
our finite field setup,

00:36:12.270 --> 00:36:18.390 align:middle line:84%
and S is smaller than
the minimum of q and X.

00:36:18.390 --> 00:36:20.030 align:middle line:90%
So either of these are trivial.

00:36:20.030 --> 00:36:23.270 align:middle line:84%
S is always at most q and
it's always at most X.

00:36:23.270 --> 00:36:28.470 align:middle line:84%
So we're make it less than that,
so we're in a non-trivial range.

00:36:28.470 --> 00:36:32.750 align:middle line:84%
Then D should be
bounded by S squared

00:36:32.750 --> 00:36:35.610 align:middle line:84%
over X, which would
be sharp if it's true,

00:36:35.610 --> 00:36:40.010 align:middle line:84%
and it matches the behavior
in an integer grid.

00:36:40.010 --> 00:36:40.510 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:40.510 --> 00:36:45.470 align:middle line:84%
This conjecture has
an analog over over--

00:36:45.470 --> 00:36:47.150 align:middle line:90%
in the real case.

00:36:47.150 --> 00:36:51.430 align:middle line:84%
And the real analog
is due to Furstenberg.

00:36:51.430 --> 00:36:54.230 align:middle line:84%
It's called the
Furstenberg set conjecture.

00:36:54.230 --> 00:37:03.100 align:middle line:84%
So it says if we have the setup
and X and D are Hausdorff,

00:37:03.100 --> 00:37:11.180 align:middle line:84%
and S is significantly less
than the minimum of R and X.

00:37:11.180 --> 00:37:13.340 align:middle line:84%
So again, S is always
smaller than R.

00:37:13.340 --> 00:37:15.900 align:middle line:84%
It's always smaller
than X. And we're

00:37:15.900 --> 00:37:20.860 align:middle line:84%
saying it's significantly less
than that, so it's non-trivial.

00:37:20.860 --> 00:37:24.140 align:middle line:84%
Then the number of
directions would

00:37:24.140 --> 00:37:29.260 align:middle line:84%
be less than tilde
tilde S squared over X.

00:37:29.260 --> 00:37:31.760 align:middle line:84%
And you see that these
conjectures again match up.

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:35.560 align:middle line:90%


00:37:35.560 --> 00:37:36.060 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:37:36.060 --> 00:37:38.580 align:middle line:90%


00:37:38.580 --> 00:37:39.260 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:40.980 align:middle line:84%
Now I mentioned on
the first day that one

00:37:40.980 --> 00:37:43.580 align:middle line:84%
of the fundamental problems
of projection theory

00:37:43.580 --> 00:37:44.980 align:middle line:90%
recently had been solved.

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:46.220 align:middle line:90%
This is the problem.

00:37:46.220 --> 00:37:49.500 align:middle line:84%
So this conjecture
has been proven.

00:37:49.500 --> 00:38:01.610 align:middle line:84%
So this is a theorem from
2024 of Orponen, Shmerkin Ren,

00:38:01.610 --> 00:38:03.930 align:middle line:90%
and Wang.

00:38:03.930 --> 00:38:05.310 align:middle line:90%
Conjecture is true.

00:38:05.310 --> 00:38:19.370 align:middle line:90%


00:38:19.370 --> 00:38:21.858 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: In the first,
the plan, it is still open?

00:38:21.858 --> 00:38:22.650 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yes.

00:38:22.650 --> 00:38:23.030 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:38:23.030 --> 00:38:23.530 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:38:23.530 --> 00:38:24.870 align:middle line:90%
Conjecture R is true.

00:38:24.870 --> 00:38:27.370 align:middle line:90%
Finite field is still wide open.

00:38:27.370 --> 00:38:29.160 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:38:29.160 --> 00:38:29.660 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:38:29.660 --> 00:38:32.810 align:middle line:90%


00:38:32.810 --> 00:38:33.955 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:38:33.955 --> 00:38:35.330 align:middle line:84%
So actually,
another reason I was

00:38:35.330 --> 00:38:37.730 align:middle line:84%
excited to do projection
theory this semester

00:38:37.730 --> 00:38:40.010 align:middle line:84%
is that a bunch
of the architects

00:38:40.010 --> 00:38:42.190 align:middle line:84%
of the recent developments
will be visiting.

00:38:42.190 --> 00:38:44.570 align:middle line:84%
Pablo Shmerkin is going to
be here for about a month.

00:38:44.570 --> 00:38:46.930 align:middle line:84%
He's going to talk in
the analysis seminar.

00:38:46.930 --> 00:38:50.010 align:middle line:84%
I might rope him into
talking in this class.

00:38:50.010 --> 00:38:52.850 align:middle line:84%
Kevin Ren is going to
visit and give a talk.

00:38:52.850 --> 00:38:55.250 align:middle line:84%
Hong will be here at some
point, although maybe not

00:38:55.250 --> 00:38:55.980 align:middle line:90%
during classes.

00:38:55.980 --> 00:38:59.760 align:middle line:90%


00:38:59.760 --> 00:39:00.680 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:02.220 align:middle line:84%
Let me say something
very briefly.

00:39:02.220 --> 00:39:04.520 align:middle line:84%
So these two conjectures,
I presented them

00:39:04.520 --> 00:39:06.620 align:middle line:90%
as being parallel to each other.

00:39:06.620 --> 00:39:08.360 align:middle line:90%
I think that's fair.

00:39:08.360 --> 00:39:12.080 align:middle line:84%
And they're both
quite difficult.

00:39:12.080 --> 00:39:15.000 align:middle line:84%
This one people have managed
to prove, which is exciting.

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.560 align:middle line:90%
And this one is still open.

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:20.660 align:middle line:84%
So the difference is
that in this problem,

00:39:20.660 --> 00:39:22.600 align:middle line:90%
there are many different scales.

00:39:22.600 --> 00:39:25.200 align:middle line:84%
We've seen the many different
scales in what we just

00:39:25.200 --> 00:39:26.478 align:middle line:90%
did with double counting.

00:39:26.478 --> 00:39:28.520 align:middle line:84%
We had to think about all
these different scales.

00:39:28.520 --> 00:39:31.200 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to do it
again with the Fourier method.

00:39:31.200 --> 00:39:33.560 align:middle line:84%
So far, you might
have the impression

00:39:33.560 --> 00:39:35.940 align:middle line:84%
that these different
scales are just a nuisance.

00:39:35.940 --> 00:39:38.440 align:middle line:84%
They make simple
arguments more complicated

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:40.600 align:middle line:90%
and the expressions longer.

00:39:40.600 --> 00:39:43.120 align:middle line:84%
But actually, having these
many different scales

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:45.560 align:middle line:90%
will turn out to be a help.

00:39:45.560 --> 00:39:48.320 align:middle line:84%
So they play a key role
in the proof of this

00:39:48.320 --> 00:39:54.140 align:middle line:84%
that, somehow, because
of all these scales,

00:39:54.140 --> 00:39:57.080 align:middle line:84%
if something goes wrong,
something has to go wrong

00:39:57.080 --> 00:39:59.620 align:middle line:90%
at many different scales.

00:39:59.620 --> 00:40:01.840 align:middle line:84%
The argument also
has different cases,

00:40:01.840 --> 00:40:04.540 align:middle line:84%
depending upon
whether the sets look

00:40:04.540 --> 00:40:06.580 align:middle line:84%
like-- set have
spacing like number one

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:07.773 align:middle line:90%
or spacing like number two.

00:40:07.773 --> 00:40:09.440 align:middle line:84%
There are different
things to play with.

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:12.060 align:middle line:84%
They're both helpful
in different ways.

00:40:12.060 --> 00:40:15.600 align:middle line:84%
And none of that structure
is available here,

00:40:15.600 --> 00:40:18.370 align:middle line:84%
so probably completely
different ideas would be needed.

00:40:18.370 --> 00:40:31.200 align:middle line:90%


00:40:31.200 --> 00:40:31.700 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:31.700 --> 00:40:32.500 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:35.380 align:middle line:84%
So the second half of
the class, the goal

00:40:35.380 --> 00:40:38.540 align:middle line:84%
is to do the Fourier
method in the real case

00:40:38.540 --> 00:40:42.460 align:middle line:90%
and build up towards doing this.

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:44.580 align:middle line:84%
Let me remind you
first of the main thing

00:40:44.580 --> 00:40:47.780 align:middle line:84%
we proved using Fourier
analysis over finite fields.

00:40:47.780 --> 00:40:51.150 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll set up a
version over the reals.

00:40:51.150 --> 00:41:17.370 align:middle line:90%


00:41:17.370 --> 00:41:17.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:17.870 --> 00:41:20.980 align:middle line:84%
So part two of the
class, Fourier method.

00:41:20.980 --> 00:41:29.250 align:middle line:90%


00:41:29.250 --> 00:41:30.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:30.130 --> 00:41:36.530 align:middle line:84%
So the main lemma that we proved
over finite fields is like this.

00:41:36.530 --> 00:41:46.570 align:middle line:84%
So let's say fancy L is a
set of lines in fq squared.

00:41:46.570 --> 00:41:51.890 align:middle line:84%
And f is a sum over
all these lines

00:41:51.890 --> 00:41:53.860 align:middle line:84%
of the characteristic
function of the line.

00:41:53.860 --> 00:41:57.880 align:middle line:90%


00:41:57.880 --> 00:41:58.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:58.760 --> 00:42:01.520 align:middle line:84%
If that's true,
then we can break up

00:42:01.520 --> 00:42:04.680 align:middle line:84%
f into two pieces, a
zero frequency piece

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:07.600 align:middle line:90%
and a non-zero frequency piece.

00:42:07.600 --> 00:42:15.160 align:middle line:84%
So then f is equal to F0
plus f-- we called it f high.

00:42:15.160 --> 00:42:16.340 align:middle line:90%
Zero frequency.

00:42:16.340 --> 00:42:17.260 align:middle line:90%
High frequency.

00:42:17.260 --> 00:42:20.040 align:middle line:90%


00:42:20.040 --> 00:42:25.120 align:middle line:84%
So the support of
f0 hat is just zero.

00:42:25.120 --> 00:42:29.280 align:middle line:90%
In other words, f0 is constant.

00:42:29.280 --> 00:42:32.400 align:middle line:84%
And we can find out exactly
what the constant is.

00:42:32.400 --> 00:42:37.600 align:middle line:84%
And based on that, we can say
that the L2 norm squared of this

00:42:37.600 --> 00:42:41.960 align:middle line:90%
is the number of lines squared.

00:42:41.960 --> 00:42:46.240 align:middle line:84%
Then the support of
the high frequency part

00:42:46.240 --> 00:42:47.770 align:middle line:90%
is the complement of zero.

00:42:47.770 --> 00:42:50.880 align:middle line:90%


00:42:50.880 --> 00:42:56.870 align:middle line:84%
And the high frequency
part has an L2 bound.

00:42:56.870 --> 00:43:00.410 align:middle line:90%
L2 squared is L times q.

00:43:00.410 --> 00:43:05.470 align:middle line:90%


00:43:05.470 --> 00:43:07.198 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:07.198 --> 00:43:11.290 align:middle line:84%
I remember teaching intro
to real analysis class once,

00:43:11.290 --> 00:43:13.790 align:middle line:84%
and so I tried to answer the
question on the first day, what

00:43:13.790 --> 00:43:15.035 align:middle line:90%
is real analysis?

00:43:15.035 --> 00:43:15.910 align:middle line:90%
So there are several.

00:43:15.910 --> 00:43:16.930 align:middle line:84%
There are lots of
different things

00:43:16.930 --> 00:43:19.350 align:middle line:84%
you might say, something
about convergence and infinity

00:43:19.350 --> 00:43:20.150 align:middle line:90%
or whatever.

00:43:20.150 --> 00:43:24.790 align:middle line:84%
But another thing I proposed
is analysis is complicated

00:43:24.790 --> 00:43:29.323 align:middle line:90%
equals simple plus small.

00:43:29.323 --> 00:43:30.490 align:middle line:90%
Study something complicated.

00:43:30.490 --> 00:43:32.190 align:middle line:84%
The real analysis
point of view is

00:43:32.190 --> 00:43:36.510 align:middle line:84%
to try to write it as something
simple plus something small.

00:43:36.510 --> 00:43:39.170 align:middle line:84%
So this is our function that
maybe we feel is complicated.

00:43:39.170 --> 00:43:40.990 align:middle line:84%
We don't understand
it that well, yet.

00:43:40.990 --> 00:43:43.050 align:middle line:90%
We wrote it as something simple.

00:43:43.050 --> 00:43:44.550 align:middle line:84%
This is a constant
function, which

00:43:44.550 --> 00:43:47.110 align:middle line:84%
makes it quite simpler
than a general function.

00:43:47.110 --> 00:43:49.030 align:middle line:84%
And then this
bit-- and the point

00:43:49.030 --> 00:43:53.860 align:middle line:84%
here is that this is
smaller than f0 or f.

00:43:53.860 --> 00:43:55.780 align:middle line:84%
Now that only becomes
true, and this only

00:43:55.780 --> 00:43:58.020 align:middle line:84%
becomes at all interesting,
when the number of lines

00:43:58.020 --> 00:44:00.420 align:middle line:90%
is much bigger than q.

00:44:00.420 --> 00:44:01.980 align:middle line:84%
When that happens,
this L2 norm is

00:44:01.980 --> 00:44:03.940 align:middle line:90%
much smaller than that L2 norm.

00:44:03.940 --> 00:44:08.620 align:middle line:84%
So complicated equals
simple plus small.

00:44:08.620 --> 00:44:10.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:10.940 --> 00:44:15.613 align:middle line:84%
So our goal is I will describe
to you the version of this lemma

00:44:15.613 --> 00:44:16.530 align:middle line:90%
over the real numbers.

00:44:16.530 --> 00:44:44.860 align:middle line:90%


00:44:44.860 --> 00:44:47.060 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:47.060 --> 00:44:51.370 align:middle line:84%
So instead of a line, so an
infinitely thin line, what we're

00:44:51.370 --> 00:44:53.270 align:middle line:84%
going to talk about
is a rectangle,

00:44:53.270 --> 00:44:55.810 align:middle line:90%
or I usually call it a tube.

00:44:55.810 --> 00:45:05.730 align:middle line:84%
So capital T for tube
is a 1 by R rectangle

00:45:05.730 --> 00:45:10.930 align:middle line:90%
in the plane in any direction.

00:45:10.930 --> 00:45:11.756 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:11.756 --> 00:45:14.850 align:middle line:84%
And so basically, we're going to
add up characteristic functions

00:45:14.850 --> 00:45:17.210 align:middle line:90%
of rectangles.

00:45:17.210 --> 00:45:19.410 align:middle line:84%
But when you do
Fourier analysis,

00:45:19.410 --> 00:45:21.530 align:middle line:84%
characteristic functions
of rectangles--

00:45:21.530 --> 00:45:24.250 align:middle line:84%
characteristic functions in
general are not super nice.

00:45:24.250 --> 00:45:27.010 align:middle line:84%
Because of the
discontinuous sharp cutoffs,

00:45:27.010 --> 00:45:29.650 align:middle line:84%
their Fourier transforms
are not very well behaved.

00:45:29.650 --> 00:45:33.690 align:middle line:84%
So what we often do is we work
with a smooth approximation

00:45:33.690 --> 00:45:36.210 align:middle line:90%
of the characteristic function.

00:45:36.210 --> 00:45:46.954 align:middle line:84%
So c sub t is a
smooth approximation

00:45:46.954 --> 00:45:52.120 align:middle line:84%
of the characteristic
function of t.

00:45:52.120 --> 00:45:53.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:53.590 --> 00:45:57.320 align:middle line:84%
So another thing about this step
of doing Fourier analysis on R2

00:45:57.320 --> 00:46:00.200 align:middle line:84%
instead of finite fields is that
certain things are a little bit

00:46:00.200 --> 00:46:00.920 align:middle line:90%
messy.

00:46:00.920 --> 00:46:03.120 align:middle line:84%
For example, it's a little
bit messy to write down

00:46:03.120 --> 00:46:06.560 align:middle line:90%
the formula for c sub t.

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:10.320 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to try the
approach of not doing

00:46:10.320 --> 00:46:12.180 align:middle line:90%
the messy details in class.

00:46:12.180 --> 00:46:14.240 align:middle line:84%
So in class I'll
give you an overview.

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:16.300 align:middle line:90%
And then on the homework.

00:46:16.300 --> 00:46:20.500 align:middle line:84%
I'll do all of the details,
and you can check the things

00:46:20.500 --> 00:46:22.250 align:middle line:84%
and make sure you
understand how it works.

00:46:22.250 --> 00:46:25.960 align:middle line:90%


00:46:25.960 --> 00:46:28.440 align:middle line:84%
And I do that partly
because I feel

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:33.560 align:middle line:84%
like sometimes the messy details
obscure the main trajectory

00:46:33.560 --> 00:46:35.280 align:middle line:90%
of what we want to do.

00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:37.720 align:middle line:84%
So it's good to first
learn what you want to do,

00:46:37.720 --> 00:46:40.200 align:middle line:84%
and then, once you know
where you're trying to go,

00:46:40.200 --> 00:46:44.080 align:middle line:84%
fill in all the little
steps to get there.

00:46:44.080 --> 00:46:47.240 align:middle line:84%
So for this class, I won't
say anything more precise than

00:46:47.240 --> 00:46:49.350 align:middle line:84%
c sub t is a smooth
approximation

00:46:49.350 --> 00:46:53.030 align:middle line:84%
of the characteristic
function of t.

00:46:53.030 --> 00:46:53.936 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:53.936 --> 00:47:01.750 align:middle line:84%
So now here is our main
lemma in the real case.

00:47:01.750 --> 00:47:02.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:02.630 --> 00:47:09.230 align:middle line:84%
So instead of L is a set
of lines, t is a set of 1

00:47:09.230 --> 00:47:14.990 align:middle line:90%
by R rectangles in the plane R2.

00:47:14.990 --> 00:47:20.230 align:middle line:84%
And then f is the sum
over all the rectangles

00:47:20.230 --> 00:47:23.670 align:middle line:84%
of this smoothed
characteristic function,

00:47:23.670 --> 00:47:28.350 align:middle line:84%
and that plays the role of
the function f up there.

00:47:28.350 --> 00:47:29.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:29.450 --> 00:47:33.190 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to break
this function up into pieces.

00:47:33.190 --> 00:47:35.230 align:middle line:84%
There are going to
be low frequency

00:47:35.230 --> 00:47:38.790 align:middle line:84%
pieces that have the advantage
of being kind of constant.

00:47:38.790 --> 00:47:41.510 align:middle line:84%
And there are going to be some
high frequency pieces that have

00:47:41.510 --> 00:47:45.230 align:middle line:90%
the advantage of being small.

00:47:45.230 --> 00:47:50.200 align:middle line:84%
But the difference between the
real world and fq is that fq,

00:47:50.200 --> 00:47:51.960 align:middle line:84%
there are only two
kinds of frequencies.

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:55.220 align:middle line:90%
There was zero and not zero.

00:47:55.220 --> 00:47:59.120 align:middle line:84%
But in the reals, there
are a lot of frequencies.

00:47:59.120 --> 00:48:03.780 align:middle line:84%
There's large, medium, small,
very small, and all of those,

00:48:03.780 --> 00:48:07.040 align:middle line:90%
they're each going to be there.

00:48:07.040 --> 00:48:07.540 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:07.540 --> 00:48:10.290 align:middle line:84%
So instead of having two pieces,
we will have many pieces.

00:48:10.290 --> 00:48:14.220 align:middle line:90%


00:48:14.220 --> 00:48:19.700 align:middle line:84%
So f is going to be
the sum of f little r.

00:48:19.700 --> 00:48:22.100 align:middle line:84%
Little r goes from
1 up to capital R

00:48:22.100 --> 00:48:25.220 align:middle line:84%
and is dyadic, just
like in theorem one.

00:48:25.220 --> 00:48:26.840 align:middle line:84%
So we'll have log
of r many pieces.

00:48:26.840 --> 00:48:29.660 align:middle line:84%
And these are the different
scales of the frequencies.

00:48:29.660 --> 00:48:30.900 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:30.900 --> 00:48:39.220 align:middle line:84%
We'll do this so that
the support of Fr hat

00:48:39.220 --> 00:48:43.820 align:middle line:84%
is contained in the ball
of radius 1 over little r.

00:48:43.820 --> 00:48:47.970 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
frequency information.

00:48:47.970 --> 00:48:51.990 align:middle line:84%
And we will say something
about the L2 norm.

00:48:51.990 --> 00:48:57.330 align:middle line:90%


00:48:57.330 --> 00:48:58.962 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:58.962 --> 00:49:03.250 align:middle line:84%
Now, our bounds on the
L2 norm before only

00:49:03.250 --> 00:49:05.570 align:middle line:84%
depended on how many
lines there were,

00:49:05.570 --> 00:49:08.130 align:middle line:84%
not about how the
lines were arranged.

00:49:08.130 --> 00:49:10.210 align:middle line:84%
But that won't be
quite true anymore.

00:49:10.210 --> 00:49:11.930 align:middle line:84%
Like we've seen in
other places, it

00:49:11.930 --> 00:49:14.730 align:middle line:84%
will matter how these
tubes are clumped.

00:49:14.730 --> 00:49:17.530 align:middle line:84%
So if you have many tubes
that are clumped together

00:49:17.530 --> 00:49:19.150 align:middle line:90%
inside of a--

00:49:19.150 --> 00:49:19.650 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:49:19.650 --> 00:49:20.150 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:20.150 --> 00:49:23.650 align:middle line:84%
So let me put the other
part of the definition.

00:49:23.650 --> 00:49:30.130 align:middle line:84%
So N sub r of T is the
maximum over T tilde, which

00:49:30.130 --> 00:49:32.370 align:middle line:84%
is like a two little
r by two big R

00:49:32.370 --> 00:49:39.130 align:middle line:84%
rectangle of the number
of T in our set of T

00:49:39.130 --> 00:49:41.530 align:middle line:84%
so that T is
contained in T tilde.

00:49:41.530 --> 00:49:44.590 align:middle line:90%
So here's a picture.

00:49:44.590 --> 00:49:46.670 align:middle line:90%
So here is T tilde.

00:49:46.670 --> 00:49:50.110 align:middle line:84%
This axis is little r
basically, and this axis

00:49:50.110 --> 00:49:52.150 align:middle line:90%
is big R, basically.

00:49:52.150 --> 00:49:54.510 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's good
to put two big R.

00:49:54.510 --> 00:49:57.390 align:middle line:84%
And inside of here there
may be a bunch of R2's.

00:49:57.390 --> 00:50:04.870 align:middle line:90%


00:50:04.870 --> 00:50:09.150 align:middle line:84%
So just like-- oh, and I guess
to be consistent with before,

00:50:09.150 --> 00:50:10.450 align:middle line:90%
I should actually do this.

00:50:10.450 --> 00:50:13.630 align:middle line:90%


00:50:13.630 --> 00:50:16.830 align:middle line:84%
So N sub X of r measured
whether many of the balls in X

00:50:16.830 --> 00:50:19.710 align:middle line:84%
were clumped together,
and N sub T of r

00:50:19.710 --> 00:50:24.130 align:middle line:84%
measures whether many of the
tubes of T are clumped together.

00:50:24.130 --> 00:50:24.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:24.630 --> 00:50:26.570 align:middle line:84%
So the bound will
depend on that thing.

00:50:26.570 --> 00:50:29.190 align:middle line:90%


00:50:29.190 --> 00:50:40.430 align:middle line:90%
Formula is-- OK.

00:50:40.430 --> 00:50:48.980 align:middle line:84%
N sub T of little r times the
number of tubes times little r

00:50:48.980 --> 00:51:00.780 align:middle line:90%
inverse times big R.

00:51:00.780 --> 00:51:01.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:01.280 --> 00:51:04.260 align:middle line:84%
So you can see that I don't
remember this formula that well.

00:51:04.260 --> 00:51:05.820 align:middle line:84%
But one thing to
notice about it is

00:51:05.820 --> 00:51:08.580 align:middle line:84%
that as this number gets
bigger, then our bound for this

00:51:08.580 --> 00:51:10.540 align:middle line:90%
gets bigger.

00:51:10.540 --> 00:51:15.940 align:middle line:84%
I also claim that this tracks
with the finite field case.

00:51:15.940 --> 00:51:19.380 align:middle line:84%
So if you plug in little
r equals 1, that's

00:51:19.380 --> 00:51:21.980 align:middle line:90%
the highest frequency part.

00:51:21.980 --> 00:51:25.660 align:middle line:84%
N sub T of 1 is
going to be just 1.

00:51:25.660 --> 00:51:28.580 align:middle line:84%
If the tubes are
disjoint, then--

00:51:28.580 --> 00:51:30.340 align:middle line:90%
or the tubes are distinct, then.

00:51:30.340 --> 00:51:31.980 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

00:51:31.980 --> 00:51:33.700 align:middle line:84%
So then if you plug
in little r equals 1,

00:51:33.700 --> 00:51:36.860 align:middle line:84%
this number will match with
the high frequency case.

00:51:36.860 --> 00:51:39.020 align:middle line:84%
And if you plug in
little r equals big R,

00:51:39.020 --> 00:51:42.322 align:middle line:84%
then this will match with
the zero frequency case.

00:51:42.322 --> 00:51:44.280 align:middle line:84%
But now we also have all
this in between stuff.

00:51:44.280 --> 00:51:50.010 align:middle line:90%


00:51:50.010 --> 00:51:52.716 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:52.716 --> 00:51:57.890 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
about this statement?

00:51:57.890 --> 00:51:59.840 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to
do a proof sketch.

00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:28.010 align:middle line:90%


00:52:28.010 --> 00:52:31.550 align:middle line:84%
Proof sketch of main lemma
are details on homework two.

00:52:31.550 --> 00:52:36.570 align:middle line:90%


00:52:36.570 --> 00:52:37.950 align:middle line:90%
How's homework one going?

00:52:37.950 --> 00:52:41.977 align:middle line:90%


00:52:41.977 --> 00:52:44.560 align:middle line:84%
If you're interested, there are
office hours after class today

00:52:44.560 --> 00:52:45.727 align:middle line:90%
and after class on Thursday.

00:52:45.727 --> 00:52:48.860 align:middle line:90%


00:52:48.860 --> 00:52:49.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:49.360 --> 00:52:56.920 align:middle line:90%


00:52:56.920 --> 00:52:57.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:57.420 --> 00:52:59.600 align:middle line:84%
There's a Fourier
analysis proof.

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:03.280 align:middle line:84%
And an important
character is, well, we'll

00:53:03.280 --> 00:53:07.000 align:middle line:84%
take the Fourier transform
of each of these CT hat.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:11.920 align:middle line:84%
And the support of CT hat is
going to be contained in T star,

00:53:11.920 --> 00:53:15.080 align:middle line:84%
where T star is
defined as follows.

00:53:15.080 --> 00:53:22.640 align:middle line:84%
It's the set of ksi in R2
so that the dot product

00:53:22.640 --> 00:53:33.360 align:middle line:84%
X1 minus X2 dot ksi has norm at
most 1 for any X1 and X2 in T.

00:53:33.360 --> 00:53:35.640 align:middle line:90%
Here's a picture.

00:53:35.640 --> 00:53:39.110 align:middle line:84%
So in X space,
here is our tube T.

00:53:39.110 --> 00:53:41.820 align:middle line:84%
And I take a couple of
points in it, X1 and X2.

00:53:41.820 --> 00:53:44.790 align:middle line:90%


00:53:44.790 --> 00:53:47.670 align:middle line:84%
So our ksi is going to
have a small dot product

00:53:47.670 --> 00:53:51.430 align:middle line:90%
with any vector like that.

00:53:51.430 --> 00:53:56.190 align:middle line:84%
And so the dimensions of
this T are-- this is 1

00:53:56.190 --> 00:54:00.550 align:middle line:90%
and this is R. OK.

00:54:00.550 --> 00:54:04.670 align:middle line:84%
Now in ksi space,
T star is going

00:54:04.670 --> 00:54:10.910 align:middle line:84%
to be perpendicular
to T. There's T star.

00:54:10.910 --> 00:54:20.830 align:middle line:84%
And it has length 1 and
width like 1 over R.

00:54:20.830 --> 00:54:26.270 align:middle line:84%
So geometrically, the idea is
that if I take my vector here,

00:54:26.270 --> 00:54:31.118 align:middle line:84%
my vector there, the long
component of this one has size R

00:54:31.118 --> 00:54:32.910 align:middle line:84%
and it gets paired with
the short component

00:54:32.910 --> 00:54:36.820 align:middle line:84%
of that one which has size 1
over R, which gives me around 1.

00:54:36.820 --> 00:54:39.140 align:middle line:84%
And the two short components--
the short component

00:54:39.140 --> 00:54:41.940 align:middle line:84%
here has size 1, which gets
paired with the long component

00:54:41.940 --> 00:54:43.160 align:middle line:90%
here, which has size 1.

00:54:43.160 --> 00:54:58.500 align:middle line:90%


00:54:58.500 --> 00:55:00.228 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:00.228 --> 00:55:02.300 align:middle line:84%
And this is analogous
to the lemma

00:55:02.300 --> 00:55:06.580 align:middle line:84%
we had in the finite field case
that the characteristic function

00:55:06.580 --> 00:55:09.460 align:middle line:84%
of a line hat was
supported in the line

00:55:09.460 --> 00:55:10.730 align:middle line:90%
perp, which is like star.

00:55:10.730 --> 00:55:17.280 align:middle line:90%


00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:17.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:17.780 --> 00:55:24.900 align:middle line:90%


00:55:24.900 --> 00:55:25.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:25.400 --> 00:55:28.143 align:middle line:90%


00:55:28.143 --> 00:55:30.060 align:middle line:84%
So that's the first
important ingredient where

00:55:30.060 --> 00:55:32.460 align:middle line:90%
the Fourier transforms live.

00:55:32.460 --> 00:55:34.530 align:middle line:84%
And I guess you're doing
the homework now where

00:55:34.530 --> 00:55:37.708 align:middle line:84%
you're checking what
line hat looks like.

00:55:37.708 --> 00:55:39.250 align:middle line:84%
And then in the next
homework, you'll

00:55:39.250 --> 00:55:40.970 align:middle line:84%
check what CT hat
looks like, and you'll

00:55:40.970 --> 00:55:42.350 align:middle line:90%
see it supported like this.

00:55:42.350 --> 00:55:44.970 align:middle line:90%


00:55:44.970 --> 00:55:46.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:46.010 --> 00:55:48.270 align:middle line:84%
So now I'll tell
you who f sub r is.

00:55:48.270 --> 00:55:51.810 align:middle line:90%


00:55:51.810 --> 00:55:54.010 align:middle line:90%
So let's next do--

00:55:54.010 --> 00:55:58.410 align:middle line:84%
so the f sub r comes from
Littlewood-Paley theory,

00:55:58.410 --> 00:56:00.330 align:middle line:84%
where you can take
any function and you

00:56:00.330 --> 00:56:03.190 align:middle line:84%
can break its frequencies
into dyadic pieces,

00:56:03.190 --> 00:56:04.610 align:middle line:90%
the Littlewood-Paley pieces.

00:56:04.610 --> 00:56:05.830 align:middle line:90%
That's what we're doing here.

00:56:05.830 --> 00:56:21.090 align:middle line:90%


00:56:21.090 --> 00:56:23.990 align:middle line:84%
So Littlewood-Paley
decomposition.

00:56:23.990 --> 00:56:27.770 align:middle line:90%


00:56:27.770 --> 00:56:36.280 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to write 1 as a
sum on my dyadic little r's

00:56:36.280 --> 00:56:38.140 align:middle line:90%
of eta r of ksi.

00:56:38.140 --> 00:56:43.040 align:middle line:84%
So this is a partition of
unity in Fourier space.

00:56:43.040 --> 00:56:47.200 align:middle line:84%
It's a partition of unity,
so these are all positive.

00:56:47.200 --> 00:56:54.680 align:middle line:84%
And the support of eta r
is contained in an annulus

00:56:54.680 --> 00:56:58.480 align:middle line:84%
where the norm of ksi is at
most 1 over r and at least 1

00:56:58.480 --> 00:57:00.600 align:middle line:90%
over 10 r.

00:57:00.600 --> 00:57:04.178 align:middle line:84%
And that's true for r
strictly between 1 and r.

00:57:04.178 --> 00:57:05.720 align:middle line:84%
And at the endpoints,
we need to have

00:57:05.720 --> 00:57:07.928 align:middle line:84%
not just an annulus but
something a little bit bigger

00:57:07.928 --> 00:57:09.960 align:middle line:90%
to cover all the frequencies.

00:57:09.960 --> 00:57:16.880 align:middle line:84%
So the support of eta capital
R is contained in the ball

00:57:16.880 --> 00:57:24.560 align:middle line:84%
of radius 1 over R, and the
support of eta 1 is contained

00:57:24.560 --> 00:57:28.980 align:middle line:84%
in the set of ksi, where the
norm of ksi is bigger than 1/10.

00:57:28.980 --> 00:57:32.390 align:middle line:90%


00:57:32.390 --> 00:57:32.930 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:57:32.930 --> 00:57:36.270 align:middle line:90%


00:57:36.270 --> 00:57:37.510 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:57:37.510 --> 00:57:39.650 align:middle line:84%
Oh, I guess maybe
I should mention.

00:57:39.650 --> 00:57:45.470 align:middle line:84%
One thing that we see from this
is that the support of f hat

00:57:45.470 --> 00:57:48.510 align:middle line:84%
is contained in the unit
ball, because every T

00:57:48.510 --> 00:57:51.010 align:middle line:90%
star is in the unit ball.

00:57:51.010 --> 00:57:56.150 align:middle line:90%


00:57:56.150 --> 00:57:57.110 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:57.110 --> 00:58:00.630 align:middle line:90%
So now I can say who fr is.

00:58:00.630 --> 00:58:04.990 align:middle line:84%
So fr is just taking f and
multiplying on the frequency

00:58:04.990 --> 00:58:06.430 align:middle line:90%
side by eta r.

00:58:06.430 --> 00:58:08.430 align:middle line:90%
So I take f hat.

00:58:08.430 --> 00:58:14.470 align:middle line:84%
I multiply it by eta r and I
take the Fourier transform back.

00:58:14.470 --> 00:58:18.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is also equal to f
convolved with eta r inverse

00:58:18.950 --> 00:58:21.590 align:middle line:90%
Fourier transform.

00:58:21.590 --> 00:58:22.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:22.130 --> 00:58:28.710 align:middle line:84%
And because this is
a partition of unity,

00:58:28.710 --> 00:58:34.070 align:middle line:84%
that tells me that f is,
indeed, the sum over r of fr.

00:58:34.070 --> 00:58:37.610 align:middle line:84%
So we can check off
our first conclusion.

00:58:37.610 --> 00:58:40.370 align:middle line:84%
And from this formula, this
here is the Fourier transform

00:58:40.370 --> 00:58:43.130 align:middle line:90%
of fr hat.

00:58:43.130 --> 00:58:46.770 align:middle line:90%
fr hat is eta r times f hat.

00:58:46.770 --> 00:58:51.570 align:middle line:84%
And that tells us that
the support of fr hat

00:58:51.570 --> 00:58:54.650 align:middle line:84%
is contained in the
ball of radius 1 over r.

00:58:54.650 --> 00:58:57.778 align:middle line:84%
So we can check off that
part of the conclusion.

00:58:57.778 --> 00:58:59.570 align:middle line:84%
And then the difficult
and interesting part

00:58:59.570 --> 00:59:09.370 align:middle line:84%
will be to figure out the L2
norm of each of these pieces fr.

00:59:09.370 --> 00:59:11.002 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:11.002 --> 00:59:14.610 align:middle line:84%
Now this operation of
localizing frequencies

00:59:14.610 --> 00:59:18.510 align:middle line:84%
to an annulus around 1 over r,
you can do it with any function,

00:59:18.510 --> 00:59:19.610 align:middle line:90%
not just with f.

00:59:19.610 --> 00:59:23.050 align:middle line:84%
So you can also do it with each
of the psi T one at a time.

00:59:23.050 --> 00:59:28.800 align:middle line:84%
So psi T comma r would
be I take psi T hat,

00:59:28.800 --> 00:59:32.760 align:middle line:84%
I multiply it by eta r, and I
take the Fourier transform back.

00:59:32.760 --> 00:59:35.880 align:middle line:84%
And so FR is the
sum over all the T

00:59:35.880 --> 00:59:38.940 align:middle line:90%
in my set of tubes of psi Tr.

00:59:38.940 --> 00:59:48.480 align:middle line:90%


00:59:48.480 --> 00:59:50.464 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:50.464 --> 00:59:52.720 align:middle line:84%
So the next thing
I'd like to do is

00:59:52.720 --> 00:59:55.360 align:middle line:84%
to visualize together
this function eta r

00:59:55.360 --> 00:59:58.020 align:middle line:90%
check and this function psi Tr.

00:59:58.020 --> 01:00:26.590 align:middle line:90%


01:00:26.590 --> 01:00:36.322 align:middle line:84%
Do a visual of eta
r check and psi Tr.

01:00:36.322 --> 01:00:39.430 align:middle line:90%


01:00:39.430 --> 01:00:40.670 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:40.670 --> 01:00:46.870 align:middle line:84%
So the function eta r itself,
eta r of ksi, that's around 1

01:00:46.870 --> 01:00:52.550 align:middle line:84%
on the annulus of
size 1 over little r.

01:00:52.550 --> 01:00:56.670 align:middle line:84%
So when I take its
inverse Fourier transform,

01:00:56.670 --> 01:01:02.830 align:middle line:84%
eta r check of x
will be around--

01:01:02.830 --> 01:01:07.910 align:middle line:84%
it will be around
1 over r squared

01:01:07.910 --> 01:01:12.630 align:middle line:90%
on most of x less than r.

01:01:12.630 --> 01:01:14.990 align:middle line:84%
So the biggest this
could possibly be

01:01:14.990 --> 01:01:18.190 align:middle line:84%
is integrating this would be
the area of this annulus, which

01:01:18.190 --> 01:01:21.430 align:middle line:90%
is 1 over r squared.

01:01:21.430 --> 01:01:23.990 align:middle line:84%
And then, because
this is smooth,

01:01:23.990 --> 01:01:27.420 align:middle line:84%
once I look at x's that are
significantly bigger than r,

01:01:27.420 --> 01:01:30.415 align:middle line:84%
I start to get a lot of
cancelation in the integral.

01:01:30.415 --> 01:01:32.040 align:middle line:84%
Let me write down
the formula for this.

01:01:32.040 --> 01:01:38.780 align:middle line:84%
So eta r check of x is the
integral e to the ix ksi

01:01:38.780 --> 01:01:40.260 align:middle line:90%
eta r of ksi.

01:01:40.260 --> 01:01:43.180 align:middle line:90%


01:01:43.180 --> 01:01:46.860 align:middle line:84%
So if x is smaller than r, there
is no significant cancelation

01:01:46.860 --> 01:01:51.460 align:middle line:84%
in this integral because
the ksi is around 1 over r.

01:01:51.460 --> 01:01:53.460 align:middle line:84%
But then when x
is bigger than r,

01:01:53.460 --> 01:01:55.640 align:middle line:84%
there starts to be
cancelation in this integral.

01:01:55.640 --> 01:01:58.700 align:middle line:84%
And because this is smooth, the
cancelation is quite dramatic.

01:01:58.700 --> 01:02:00.170 align:middle line:90%
So this is rapidly decaying.

01:02:00.170 --> 01:02:03.740 align:middle line:90%


01:02:03.740 --> 01:02:04.490 align:middle line:90%
x bigger.

01:02:04.490 --> 01:02:07.030 align:middle line:90%


01:02:07.030 --> 01:02:11.900 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's what the size
of this function is like.

01:02:11.900 --> 01:02:15.740 align:middle line:84%
But also there's some
cancelation in it.

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:19.000 align:middle line:84%
So if you integrate
this function.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:21.580 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you integrate
that, you get

01:02:21.580 --> 01:02:25.930 align:middle line:84%
eta r of 0, which is 0
because eta r is supported

01:02:25.930 --> 01:02:27.530 align:middle line:90%
on an annulus and not a ball.

01:02:27.530 --> 01:02:29.810 align:middle line:84%
So this function has
some cancelation in it.

01:02:29.810 --> 01:02:31.030 align:middle line:90%
It averages to 0.

01:02:31.030 --> 01:02:35.010 align:middle line:90%


01:02:35.010 --> 01:02:35.510 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:35.510 --> 01:02:40.430 align:middle line:90%


01:02:40.430 --> 01:02:43.490 align:middle line:90%
So I can graph it.

01:02:43.490 --> 01:02:47.010 align:middle line:90%
Ksi sub r check is radial.

01:02:47.010 --> 01:02:53.570 align:middle line:84%
So here is the radius norm of
x and here's eta r check of x.

01:02:53.570 --> 01:02:56.060 align:middle line:84%
And it would look
something like this.

01:02:56.060 --> 01:02:59.410 align:middle line:90%


01:02:59.410 --> 01:03:01.350 align:middle line:84%
And you have to
do this carefully,

01:03:01.350 --> 01:03:04.010 align:middle line:84%
but the negative part is going
to balance the positive part

01:03:04.010 --> 01:03:05.410 align:middle line:90%
to integrate to 0.

01:03:05.410 --> 01:03:06.910 align:middle line:90%
So imagine rotating this.

01:03:06.910 --> 01:03:10.250 align:middle line:90%


01:03:10.250 --> 01:03:12.990 align:middle line:90%
And this scale here, that's r.

01:03:12.990 --> 01:03:22.480 align:middle line:90%


01:03:22.480 --> 01:03:23.466 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:23.466 --> 01:03:27.960 align:middle line:84%
Now these different
exponents here

01:03:27.960 --> 01:03:34.180 align:middle line:84%
work out nicely and
a different way--

01:03:34.180 --> 01:03:36.720 align:middle line:84%
a way to describe
it is that if I

01:03:36.720 --> 01:03:43.240 align:middle line:84%
take the integral of the norm
of eta r check of x dx, well,

01:03:43.240 --> 01:03:46.400 align:middle line:84%
it's around 1 over r squared
times the area of the ball

01:03:46.400 --> 01:03:49.560 align:middle line:90%
of radius r, which is 1.

01:03:49.560 --> 01:03:52.880 align:middle line:90%
That integral is around 1.

01:03:52.880 --> 01:03:56.040 align:middle line:84%
So if I were to
take some function

01:03:56.040 --> 01:03:58.920 align:middle line:84%
and convolve it with the
absolute value of eta r

01:03:58.920 --> 01:04:05.320 align:middle line:84%
check of x, that would roughly
be the average value of f

01:04:05.320 --> 01:04:08.240 align:middle line:84%
on the ball around
x of radius r.

01:04:08.240 --> 01:04:11.020 align:middle line:84%
The weighted average is not
exactly the standard average,

01:04:11.020 --> 01:04:12.860 align:middle line:90%
but that's roughly what it is.

01:04:12.860 --> 01:04:17.360 align:middle line:90%


01:04:17.360 --> 01:04:22.990 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So is it the case
that convolution with a function

01:04:22.990 --> 01:04:25.410 align:middle line:90%
on the annu--

01:04:25.410 --> 01:04:29.150 align:middle line:84%
like, if eta r is
on the annulus,

01:04:29.150 --> 01:04:34.210 align:middle line:84%
basically behaves the same as if
it were on the ball of radius.

01:04:34.210 --> 01:04:37.712 align:middle line:90%


01:04:37.712 --> 01:04:39.670 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So the
question is, how would we

01:04:39.670 --> 01:04:42.590 align:middle line:84%
compare an eta r that's
supported on an annulus

01:04:42.590 --> 01:04:46.830 align:middle line:84%
with a similar function that
was supported on the whole ball?

01:04:46.830 --> 01:04:47.470 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:04:47.470 --> 01:04:48.950 align:middle line:90%
It's mostly similar.

01:04:48.950 --> 01:04:51.750 align:middle line:84%
Because of the annulus,
there's more cancelation.

01:04:51.750 --> 01:04:53.310 align:middle line:84%
So if we did it
on the whole ball,

01:04:53.310 --> 01:04:57.190 align:middle line:84%
we wouldn't have this
integral property.

01:04:57.190 --> 01:04:59.198 align:middle line:84%
There may or may not be
a little negative part

01:04:59.198 --> 01:05:00.490 align:middle line:90%
if we did it on the whole ball.

01:05:00.490 --> 01:05:01.590 align:middle line:84%
But the negative
part would probably

01:05:01.590 --> 01:05:03.320 align:middle line:84%
would be dominated
by the positive part.

01:05:03.320 --> 01:05:10.030 align:middle line:90%


01:05:10.030 --> 01:05:10.722 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:10.722 --> 01:05:13.500 align:middle line:84%
So that's what the
function eta r looks like.

01:05:13.500 --> 01:05:17.630 align:middle line:90%


01:05:17.630 --> 01:05:19.300 align:middle line:84%
And now that we
understand that, we

01:05:19.300 --> 01:05:23.780 align:middle line:84%
can understand the
function psi Tr

01:05:23.780 --> 01:05:30.360 align:middle line:84%
because psi Tr is equal to psi
T convolved with eta r check.

01:05:30.360 --> 01:05:32.980 align:middle line:90%


01:05:32.980 --> 01:05:33.912 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:33.912 --> 01:05:40.420 align:middle line:84%
So the norm of psi Tr of x
is around r inverse times

01:05:40.420 --> 01:05:45.020 align:middle line:84%
the characteristic function
of a thickened tube.

01:05:45.020 --> 01:05:49.580 align:middle line:84%
So if I take the r
neighborhood of T.

01:05:49.580 --> 01:05:57.260 align:middle line:84%
So if this is T I could
take a fat neighborhood

01:05:57.260 --> 01:06:03.100 align:middle line:90%
of that that looks like this.

01:06:03.100 --> 01:06:06.780 align:middle line:84%
So that's the r
neighborhood of T.

01:06:06.780 --> 01:06:09.780 align:middle line:84%
So psi T itself is basically
supported on T, although it's

01:06:09.780 --> 01:06:11.180 align:middle line:90%
smoothed out a little bit.

01:06:11.180 --> 01:06:13.780 align:middle line:84%
And then when I take
the low frequency

01:06:13.780 --> 01:06:17.810 align:middle line:84%
part, the 1 over r frequency
part, then it gets spread out

01:06:17.810 --> 01:06:19.040 align:middle line:90%
and it gets smaller.

01:06:19.040 --> 01:06:22.610 align:middle line:90%


01:06:22.610 --> 01:06:23.356 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:23.356 --> 01:06:27.290 align:middle line:84%
And it also has some
cancelation in it.

01:06:27.290 --> 01:06:30.210 align:middle line:84%
So if the graph of
this function mostly

01:06:30.210 --> 01:06:33.410 align:middle line:84%
depends on the transverse
direction, and then

01:06:33.410 --> 01:06:34.462 align:middle line:90%
it looks a lot like this.

01:06:34.462 --> 01:06:36.170 align:middle line:84%
So this would be the
transverse direction

01:06:36.170 --> 01:06:37.378 align:middle line:90%
and this would be the height.

01:06:37.378 --> 01:06:39.898 align:middle line:90%


01:06:39.898 --> 01:06:41.440 align:middle line:84%
So here I'll put
that in the picture.

01:06:41.440 --> 01:06:45.610 align:middle line:90%


01:06:45.610 --> 01:06:49.730 align:middle line:84%
So this transverse
direction maybe I'll call y.

01:06:49.730 --> 01:06:52.810 align:middle line:84%
And then we could make a
graph where here we put y,

01:06:52.810 --> 01:06:57.330 align:middle line:90%
and here we put psi Tr of y.

01:06:57.330 --> 01:07:00.370 align:middle line:90%
And we would see the same thing.

01:07:00.370 --> 01:07:01.730 align:middle line:90%
Positive.

01:07:01.730 --> 01:07:02.430 align:middle line:90%
Negative.

01:07:02.430 --> 01:07:07.110 align:middle line:90%


01:07:07.110 --> 01:07:10.370 align:middle line:90%
And this length scale here is r.

01:07:10.370 --> 01:07:12.950 align:middle line:84%
The negative part would
cancel the positive part,

01:07:12.950 --> 01:07:15.230 align:middle line:84%
because if you
convolve something

01:07:15.230 --> 01:07:18.590 align:middle line:84%
who integrates to 0
with something else,

01:07:18.590 --> 01:07:20.930 align:middle line:84%
then the whole thing
will integrate to 0.

01:07:20.930 --> 01:07:25.910 align:middle line:90%


01:07:25.910 --> 01:07:26.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:07:26.710 --> 01:07:29.290 align:middle line:84%
So that's what these
functions look like.

01:07:29.290 --> 01:07:35.770 align:middle line:90%


01:07:35.770 --> 01:07:36.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:07:36.270 --> 01:07:45.070 align:middle line:90%


01:07:45.070 --> 01:07:45.850 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:07:45.850 --> 01:07:51.270 align:middle line:90%


01:07:51.270 --> 01:07:53.270 align:middle line:84%
So before I erase
this, maybe I'll say.

01:07:53.270 --> 01:07:54.870 align:middle line:84%
So we mentioned
earlier that if we

01:07:54.870 --> 01:07:57.790 align:middle line:84%
have a smooth function
supported on this tube,

01:07:57.790 --> 01:07:59.490 align:middle line:90%
we take its Fourier transform.

01:07:59.490 --> 01:08:02.670 align:middle line:84%
It's essentially supported
on this dual tube.

01:08:02.670 --> 01:08:04.790 align:middle line:84%
That proof is a
slightly fancier version

01:08:04.790 --> 01:08:06.773 align:middle line:84%
of what we were
just talking about.

01:08:06.773 --> 01:08:08.190 align:middle line:84%
So we were just
saying that if you

01:08:08.190 --> 01:08:11.070 align:middle line:84%
have a smooth function
on a certain annulus

01:08:11.070 --> 01:08:14.900 align:middle line:84%
or a certain ball, then its
Fourier transform is essentially

01:08:14.900 --> 01:08:16.660 align:middle line:84%
supported on a
dual ball and then

01:08:16.660 --> 01:08:19.819 align:middle line:90%
its rapidly decaying outside.

01:08:19.819 --> 01:08:23.479 align:middle line:84%
So this first statement is
exactly the same as that,

01:08:23.479 --> 01:08:26.140 align:middle line:84%
except that we have a
tube instead of a ball.

01:08:26.140 --> 01:08:28.660 align:middle line:84%
Having a tube instead of a ball
makes it a little-- there's

01:08:28.660 --> 01:08:30.812 align:middle line:84%
a little bit more writing
or thinking involved,

01:08:30.812 --> 01:08:31.770 align:middle line:90%
but it's the same idea.

01:08:31.770 --> 01:08:34.769 align:middle line:90%


01:08:34.769 --> 01:08:36.269 align:middle line:84%
The details will
be on the homework.

01:08:36.269 --> 01:08:38.880 align:middle line:90%


01:08:38.880 --> 01:08:39.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:39.380 --> 01:08:45.859 align:middle line:90%


01:08:45.859 --> 01:08:46.580 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:46.580 --> 01:08:52.180 align:middle line:84%
So in the finite
field case, the heart

01:08:52.180 --> 01:08:53.899 align:middle line:84%
of the argument,
the key thing called

01:08:53.899 --> 01:08:56.620 align:middle line:84%
the key lemma was an
orthogonality lemma that

01:08:56.620 --> 01:08:59.220 align:middle line:84%
said that the high frequency
parts two different lines

01:08:59.220 --> 01:09:00.740 align:middle line:90%
are orthogonal.

01:09:00.740 --> 01:09:04.660 align:middle line:84%
And something like
that is true here.

01:09:04.660 --> 01:09:07.700 align:middle line:90%
So lemma on orthogonality.

01:09:07.700 --> 01:09:10.100 align:middle line:90%
This is like the key lemma.

01:09:10.100 --> 01:09:11.560 align:middle line:90%
So it says the following.

01:09:11.560 --> 01:09:14.330 align:middle line:90%


01:09:14.330 --> 01:09:17.899 align:middle line:84%
T1 and T2 are
tubes, 1 by R tubes.

01:09:17.899 --> 01:09:22.290 align:middle line:90%


01:09:22.290 --> 01:09:27.550 align:middle line:84%
Then the psi Tr's are
usually orthogonal.

01:09:27.550 --> 01:09:35.290 align:middle line:84%
So if I take the inner product
of psi T1r with psi T2r,

01:09:35.290 --> 01:09:39.170 align:middle line:90%
it's usually really small.

01:09:39.170 --> 01:09:41.689 align:middle line:84%
R to the minus 1,000, something
that's really small compared

01:09:41.689 --> 01:09:46.569 align:middle line:84%
to everything in our proof,
unless the two tubes are quite

01:09:46.569 --> 01:09:47.689 align:middle line:90%
similar.

01:09:47.689 --> 01:09:50.770 align:middle line:84%
And the way we'll
say this is there

01:09:50.770 --> 01:09:58.370 align:middle line:84%
exists T tilde, which is just
basically a little r by big R

01:09:58.370 --> 01:09:59.130 align:middle line:90%
tube.

01:09:59.130 --> 01:10:02.978 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to magnify it
just a little bit that.

01:10:02.978 --> 01:10:04.530 align:middle line:90%
That contains them both.

01:10:04.530 --> 01:10:11.282 align:middle line:90%


01:10:11.282 --> 01:10:14.120 align:middle line:90%
T tilde and inside of here.

01:10:14.120 --> 01:10:16.460 align:middle line:90%
And they have these T1 and T2.

01:10:16.460 --> 01:10:23.540 align:middle line:90%


01:10:23.540 --> 01:10:24.040 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:24.040 --> 01:10:25.880 align:middle line:84%
So we could have some
intuition about this

01:10:25.880 --> 01:10:29.160 align:middle line:84%
from our visualization
of psi Tr.

01:10:29.160 --> 01:10:34.215 align:middle line:84%
If I were to take T1 and
T2 in the same T tilde--

01:10:34.215 --> 01:10:35.840 align:middle line:84%
so this thickened
neighborhood, notice,

01:10:35.840 --> 01:10:38.000 align:middle line:84%
is basically the
same as T tilde.

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:41.400 align:middle line:84%
If I pick T1 and T2
corresponding to the same T

01:10:41.400 --> 01:10:44.640 align:middle line:84%
tilde, then when I
thicken them both,

01:10:44.640 --> 01:10:47.680 align:middle line:84%
I get basically
the same rectangle.

01:10:47.680 --> 01:10:51.280 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, then the
functions psi T1r and psi T2r

01:10:51.280 --> 01:10:53.960 align:middle line:84%
are basically the same
function, so they are not

01:10:53.960 --> 01:10:56.440 align:middle line:90%
at all orthogonal.

01:10:56.440 --> 01:10:59.680 align:middle line:84%
And that's the only
thing that can go wrong

01:10:59.680 --> 01:11:02.400 align:middle line:84%
if the thickened neighborhoods
are disjoint or certainly

01:11:02.400 --> 01:11:03.840 align:middle line:90%
orthogonal.

01:11:03.840 --> 01:11:05.440 align:middle line:84%
And the more
interesting part is that

01:11:05.440 --> 01:11:08.360 align:middle line:84%
if the thickened neighborhoods
are transverse to each other,

01:11:08.360 --> 01:11:09.650 align:middle line:90%
they are orthogonal.

01:11:09.650 --> 01:11:12.270 align:middle line:90%


01:11:12.270 --> 01:11:16.850 align:middle line:84%
And we can check that
by Fourier analysis.

01:11:16.850 --> 01:11:19.510 align:middle line:90%


01:11:19.510 --> 01:11:20.380 align:middle line:90%
So proof sketch.

01:11:20.380 --> 01:11:30.715 align:middle line:90%


01:11:30.715 --> 01:11:38.230 align:middle line:84%
If the angle between
T1 and T2 is bigger

01:11:38.230 --> 01:11:41.550 align:middle line:84%
than maybe r to the
epsilon 1 over R--

01:11:41.550 --> 01:11:50.190 align:middle line:84%
or little r over big R,
then the support of psi

01:11:50.190 --> 01:12:01.830 align:middle line:84%
Tr hat intersected the support
of T1 of psi T2r hat is empty.

01:12:01.830 --> 01:12:05.190 align:middle line:90%
So the support of psi T1--

01:12:05.190 --> 01:12:11.460 align:middle line:84%
so this is the support
of psi T1 hat intersected

01:12:11.460 --> 01:12:15.700 align:middle line:84%
with the annulus of size
1 over r, intersected

01:12:15.700 --> 01:12:20.020 align:middle line:90%
with the support of psi T2 hat.

01:12:20.020 --> 01:12:21.620 align:middle line:84%
And these are two
rectangles that

01:12:21.620 --> 01:12:24.060 align:middle line:90%
are transverse to each other.

01:12:24.060 --> 01:12:28.420 align:middle line:84%
And so you can check the
intersection is empty.

01:12:28.420 --> 01:12:30.340 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why does it
rule out the translation

01:12:30.340 --> 01:12:33.027 align:middle line:84%
for the rectangles if
they're [INAUDIBLE]?

01:12:33.027 --> 01:12:33.860 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:12:33.860 --> 01:12:35.400 align:middle line:90%
And so that's case one.

01:12:35.400 --> 01:12:41.740 align:middle line:84%
So the other case is if
the R neighborhood of T1

01:12:41.740 --> 01:12:48.460 align:middle line:84%
is disjoint from the
R neighborhood of T2

01:12:48.460 --> 01:12:51.740 align:middle line:84%
or a little bit
more than r, then

01:12:51.740 --> 01:12:58.420 align:middle line:84%
we use the formula
psi Tr is psi T1.

01:12:58.420 --> 01:13:05.015 align:middle line:84%
So then we have here
integral psi T1r,

01:13:05.015 --> 01:13:09.110 align:middle line:84%
psi T2r, complex
conjugate, is the integral

01:13:09.110 --> 01:13:17.050 align:middle line:84%
of psi T1 convolved with eta
1 and psi T2 convolved eta r

01:13:17.050 --> 01:13:18.170 align:middle line:90%
check.

01:13:18.170 --> 01:13:20.500 align:middle line:84%
And these two guys
have disjoint support.

01:13:20.500 --> 01:13:48.290 align:middle line:90%


01:13:48.290 --> 01:13:49.954 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:49.954 --> 01:13:54.730 align:middle line:84%
So now we are ready to
estimate the L2 norm.

01:13:54.730 --> 01:13:58.890 align:middle line:84%
So our orthogonality lemma says
that these different psi Tr's

01:13:58.890 --> 01:14:02.310 align:middle line:84%
are usually orthogonal
with a few exceptions.

01:14:02.310 --> 01:14:04.290 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
use that orthogonality

01:14:04.290 --> 01:14:06.480 align:middle line:84%
to estimate the L2
norm, but we have

01:14:06.480 --> 01:14:08.580 align:middle line:84%
to keep track of how many
exceptions there are.

01:14:08.580 --> 01:14:28.320 align:middle line:90%


01:14:28.320 --> 01:14:28.980 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:14:28.980 --> 01:14:30.500 align:middle line:90%
So L2 estimate.

01:14:30.500 --> 01:14:34.000 align:middle line:90%


01:14:34.000 --> 01:14:38.440 align:middle line:84%
So the last thing we need
to check is fr L2 squared.

01:14:38.440 --> 01:14:44.760 align:middle line:84%
So fr is the sum over
all of our T of psi Tr.

01:14:44.760 --> 01:14:47.200 align:middle line:90%
L2 squared.

01:14:47.200 --> 01:14:50.420 align:middle line:84%
So that's this thing
inner product with itself.

01:14:50.420 --> 01:14:54.440 align:middle line:84%
So if I expand it
out, it's the sum T1,

01:14:54.440 --> 01:15:02.990 align:middle line:84%
T2 of the inner product
of psi T1r, psi T2r.

01:15:02.990 --> 01:15:08.590 align:middle line:90%


01:15:08.590 --> 01:15:09.576 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:09.576 --> 01:15:11.750 align:middle line:84%
And the key point
is orthogonality

01:15:11.750 --> 01:15:14.710 align:middle line:84%
lemma tells us that most of
the inner products in this sum

01:15:14.710 --> 01:15:16.030 align:middle line:90%
are negligible.

01:15:16.030 --> 01:15:18.110 align:middle line:90%
There's only a few that are not.

01:15:18.110 --> 01:15:21.130 align:middle line:84%
Let me give a bit of a name
to the ones that are not.

01:15:21.130 --> 01:15:29.030 align:middle line:90%


01:15:29.030 --> 01:15:36.230 align:middle line:84%
So this scenario here,
I'm going to abbreviate it

01:15:36.230 --> 01:15:41.390 align:middle line:84%
as saying that T1
is related to T2.

01:15:41.390 --> 01:15:43.910 align:middle line:90%
T1 is close to T2.

01:15:43.910 --> 01:15:46.630 align:middle line:84%
I guess we could
put a little r here.

01:15:46.630 --> 01:15:49.230 align:middle line:84%
So this inner
product is negligible

01:15:49.230 --> 01:15:52.470 align:middle line:90%
unless T1 is related to T2.

01:15:52.470 --> 01:15:54.198 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:54.198 --> 01:15:56.800 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at our big
sum of inner products.

01:15:56.800 --> 01:16:00.390 align:middle line:90%


01:16:00.390 --> 01:16:02.890 align:middle line:84%
And I'll break it
up into two parts.

01:16:02.890 --> 01:16:08.770 align:middle line:84%
It's the sum where T1 is
related to T2 inner product,

01:16:08.770 --> 01:16:10.230 align:middle line:90%
plus the rest of them.

01:16:10.230 --> 01:16:13.310 align:middle line:84%
And the rest of them are really
tiny by the orthogonality lemma,

01:16:13.310 --> 01:16:14.950 align:middle line:84%
so the rest of them
are negligible.

01:16:14.950 --> 01:16:20.090 align:middle line:90%


01:16:20.090 --> 01:16:20.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:20.590 --> 01:16:23.310 align:middle line:84%
Now each of these inner
products, all arithmetic,

01:16:23.310 --> 01:16:24.730 align:middle line:90%
geometric mean it.

01:16:24.730 --> 01:16:33.050 align:middle line:84%
So that's less than the sum
T1 related to T2 of psi Tr L2

01:16:33.050 --> 01:16:40.080 align:middle line:84%
squared psi T1r L2 squared
plus psi T2r L2 squared.

01:16:40.080 --> 01:16:45.610 align:middle line:90%


01:16:45.610 --> 01:16:46.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:46.350 --> 01:16:50.510 align:middle line:84%
So I want to know how many times
does each of these functions psi

01:16:50.510 --> 01:16:53.250 align:middle line:90%
T1 appear in this sum.

01:16:53.250 --> 01:16:56.370 align:middle line:84%
And the number of times is the
number of different T2's that

01:16:56.370 --> 01:16:58.770 align:middle line:90%
are related to T1.

01:16:58.770 --> 01:17:02.160 align:middle line:84%
And that number is
basically the number

01:17:02.160 --> 01:17:03.550 align:middle line:90%
that appears in our main lemma.

01:17:03.550 --> 01:17:06.120 align:middle line:90%


01:17:06.120 --> 01:17:07.780 align:middle line:84%
This thing that we
were counting here,

01:17:07.780 --> 01:17:12.160 align:middle line:84%
how many tubes lie in a
little r by big R big tube?

01:17:12.160 --> 01:17:17.040 align:middle line:84%
That's exactly how many
tubes T2 are related to T1.

01:17:17.040 --> 01:17:18.060 align:middle line:90%
So this thing.

01:17:18.060 --> 01:17:21.600 align:middle line:90%


01:17:21.600 --> 01:17:29.080 align:middle line:84%
You can say the number of T2
so that T2 is related to T1.

01:17:29.080 --> 01:17:34.920 align:middle line:84%
This is bounded by Nr
of T. So this whole sum

01:17:34.920 --> 01:17:42.880 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by Nr of T times
just the sum on all the T and T

01:17:42.880 --> 01:17:45.570 align:middle line:90%
of psi Tr L2 squared.

01:17:45.570 --> 01:17:55.520 align:middle line:90%


01:17:55.520 --> 01:17:56.080 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:17:56.080 --> 01:17:57.788 align:middle line:84%
And then finally, each
of these functions

01:17:57.788 --> 01:18:00.070 align:middle line:90%
we've already described.

01:18:00.070 --> 01:18:03.870 align:middle line:90%
So hopefully I didn't erase it.

01:18:03.870 --> 01:18:04.630 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:18:04.630 --> 01:18:05.610 align:middle line:90%
So we described it.

01:18:05.610 --> 01:18:08.990 align:middle line:84%
It has height at r inverse, and
it's supported on a little r

01:18:08.990 --> 01:18:10.470 align:middle line:90%
by big R rectangle.

01:18:10.470 --> 01:18:12.410 align:middle line:90%
So we can compute its L2 norm.

01:18:12.410 --> 01:18:15.390 align:middle line:90%


01:18:15.390 --> 01:18:22.670 align:middle line:84%
So this is N sub T of r times
the number of tubes times

01:18:22.670 --> 01:18:24.330 align:middle line:90%
the height was r inverse.

01:18:24.330 --> 01:18:28.550 align:middle line:84%
So that's r to the
minus 2 times the--

01:18:28.550 --> 01:18:32.310 align:middle line:84%
so this is the
amplitude squared.

01:18:32.310 --> 01:18:40.370 align:middle line:84%
And this is the area
for this psi Tr.

01:18:40.370 --> 01:18:42.690 align:middle line:84%
And that was the thing that
was on the right hand side.

01:18:42.690 --> 01:18:45.510 align:middle line:90%


01:18:45.510 --> 01:18:46.110 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:18:46.110 --> 01:18:50.390 align:middle line:84%
Let me summarize the
proof for the last minute.

01:18:50.390 --> 01:18:52.370 align:middle line:84%
Let's look back at
our statement here.

01:18:52.370 --> 01:18:57.900 align:middle line:90%


01:18:57.900 --> 01:19:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So if we look at
this sum of tubes,

01:19:00.680 --> 01:19:03.380 align:middle line:84%
we're going to break it into
different frequency pieces.

01:19:03.380 --> 01:19:05.020 align:middle line:90%
Littlewood-Paley theory.

01:19:05.020 --> 01:19:08.740 align:middle line:84%
And then the high
frequency pieces

01:19:08.740 --> 01:19:12.100 align:middle line:84%
are usually orthogonal
to each other.

01:19:12.100 --> 01:19:15.060 align:middle line:84%
If you look at two tubes and
you look at the frequency 1

01:19:15.060 --> 01:19:19.140 align:middle line:84%
over r part, they're orthogonal
to each other unless those two

01:19:19.140 --> 01:19:23.660 align:middle line:84%
tubes are in a common fat
tube, little r by big R.

01:19:23.660 --> 01:19:26.660 align:middle line:84%
And so you take advantage
of that orthogonality where

01:19:26.660 --> 01:19:28.490 align:middle line:84%
it's available and
it gives this bound.

01:19:28.490 --> 01:19:37.440 align:middle line:90%


01:19:37.440 --> 01:19:37.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:19:37.940 --> 01:19:38.540 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:19:38.540 --> 01:19:40.220 align:middle line:90%
Let's stop there for today.

01:19:40.220 --> 01:19:44.260 align:middle line:84%
We will wrap this up on
Thursday and then discuss

01:19:44.260 --> 01:19:47.100 align:middle line:84%
how similar ideas apply
in a different context

01:19:47.100 --> 01:19:48.220 align:middle line:90%
in sieve theory.

01:19:48.220 --> 01:19:50.570 align:middle line:90%
In number theory.

01:19:50.570 --> 01:19:56.000 align:middle line:90%